The shelled Higgs boson
The announcement of the probable discovery of the Higgs boson created quite a stir, last summer, and for good reason.
Indeed, it is believed that this boson participates in the mechanism responsible for the mass of everything in the Universe, just that.
And then, this is the last particle whose existence is predicted by the Standard Model - our best, or "less worst" explanation of the nature and behavior of matter - but which has not yet been observed empirically.
But for physicists, it is not yet completely certain that it is the Higgs.
We know beyond a shadow of a doubt that we are holding an authentic new particle, and that it looks very much like the Higgs boson predicted by the Standard Model.
In addition, new data unveiled this week at a major physics conference in Kyoto seem to confirm this, but there is still a lack of data to be completely certain.
Let’s assume it’s the Higgs anyway, since the chances of getting it wrong seem slim, and let’s see what it’s all about.
There is, in this low world, a fatally inescapable law that two things cannot be in the same place at the same time.
No way to break this rule - and don't try too hard, you're going to hurt yourself.
Even if particle physics is a very strange world, it turns out that it also has a law of this kind: the Pauli exclusion principle, which states that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state" - this "state" consisting roughly of some of their characteristics.
From there, physicists classify particles into two categories.
In one corner there are good citizens named fermions, who wisely obey the principle of Pauli.
And in the other are the bosons, a dirty bunch of anarchists who have no respect for anything - at least not for this principle, which means they can be in the same place at the same time.
These bosons then divide into two groups, according to the (absolutely extraordinary, by the way) site The Particle Adventure, of Berkeley Laboratories: the mesons, which we will not address here, and the "particles of force", by which the great forces of nature propagate and to which the Higgs boson would be somehow related.
These bosons, it must be emphasized here, are not all creatures as exotic as one might think.
In fact, if you manage to read this chronicle, it is thanks to a boson of an extraordinary banality: the photon, or the "particle of light" that is the "messenger" of the electromagnetic force.
When, in fact, a particle with an electric charge accelerates or changes direction, it "disturbs" the electromagnetic field in this precise place, a bit like a pebble thrown into a pond.
From this "disturbation" arises an electromagnetic wave (light, or infrared, or ultraviolet, etc.), and this wave is nothing more than a photon - and therefore, one of the "force-carrying" bosons.
More stable field
The same is true for the Higgs boson, except that it is another field, the Higgs field, that must be "disturbed" for this boson to appear.
Now, this Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; to excite it, one must reach very, very high energies, a bit like a frozen pond whose surface could only be wrinkled by a very large rock.
That's why it takes a huge particle accelerator like CERN's - the Large Hadron Collider is a ring 27 km in circumference! - to reach such energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is again useful to explain the relationship between the Higgs and mass.
Not all particles, nor all materials, interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do, but others do not - a piece of paper, for example, will never hold itself on a fridge.
And in the same way, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that do have a mass, while the others (like the photon, tiens) do not.
Now, what "can bring" all this research, Ms. Plamondon asks?
For science, this serves to verify the validity of the Standard Model (SM), and it also allows physicists to scrutinize any gap between the observations and predictions of the SM.
In fact, there are many who strongly wish that we find them, because the slightest difference could open a door on a "new physics" and plug some holes in the Model.
This one, it must be said, still has huge shortcomings, offering no explanation for gravity (oops!) or dark matter, which forms about 80% of the matter of the Universe (re-oops!).
But no such gaps have been found at CERN so far.
Implications
The repercussions of this research in the daily life of Mr. and Mrs. Tout-le-Monde, they are more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that there will be none.
In the early 1960s, the pioneers of lasers at Bell Laboratories had no idea of the revolution their work would spark.
They saw scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, the late physicist Willard Boyle - who worked at Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who himself developed the first continuous laser (the first were pulsed), in 1962 - initially the laser was rather seen as a "lab gadget".
I can imagine...
And then, the applications can also come from all the instrumentation that surrounds the research.
For example, the same Willard Boyle developed a small light sensor in 1969, during his work in optics.
This sensor, although not its original intent at all, now serves as the “eye” for all digital cameras in the world, and earned it the 2009 Nobel Prize in Physics.
This of course does not mean that the activities of the LHC will necessarily transform our lives, but it does mean that, really, you never know...
