Le Devoir tried to take a closer look.
Just a few weeks ago, Mr. L. was still living alone in his apartment in the Montérégie.
The prostate cancer that was gnawing at him had given him a two-year reprieve.
“They had given me five years to live, I turned seven,” he said, half-figure half-grape, lying in his bed at the Victor-Gadbois palliative care home in Beloeil, where he arrived the day before.
“But it’s always a shock, you can’t be prepared for that,” he says.
The disease does its work: a huge weakness that prevents him from going to the toilet alone, and even eating alone.
Seated in front of an appetizing lunch, he agrees to let himself be helped to eat, resigned.
Courageous, he even manages to smile, speaks to strangers who are busy around him, bring him his medicines, offer him a bath.
The courage of ordinary death.
“My biggest wish is to be cured of diarrhea, it’s humiliating,” he confides.
A few hours later, the team found a cure for this ailment.
"In the course of our lives, we learn that a man pees standing up," says Pierre Brodeur, a psychologist at the Victor-Gadbois house.
Going back to the child’s stage, for some people, is an unacceptable humiliation.
"It depends on the person's ability" to accept regression, he notes.
Because, in the opinion of several people working in palliative care, great moments are taking place at the very heart of this regression.
Patients who enter the Victor-Gadbois hospice all have cancer.
They have a maximum life expectancy of three months.
At this point, the "team of doctors and nurses around them no longer provide so-called "curative" care.
For Ms. A., 89, the worst fear is to die "conscious and suffocated".
But the disease made me discover my children.
“I have good children,” she adds.
“I have no wishes in life,” she says, before agreeing to have a mask put on to help her breathe.
In the coming days, however, she is expecting a last visit from her son from Italy.
In Victor-Gadbois, along with a group of volunteers, body care and food assistance are provided.
These are palliative care, which is given when there is nothing else to do.
To make death more comfortable.
In Quebec, there is one palliative care bed for 11,700 inhabitants.
It's very little when you know that we all end up dying one day.
Here, life goes on in the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the doctors in the house.
Whether on the level of physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
When dying, it will be agreed to provide mouth care to brandy or Pepsi, depending on the request.
Diabetics will no longer be required to control their sugar levels.
Death is part of everyday life.
Last night, we served a beer to Mr. X, who passed away last night.
This morning, it is his son who will finish the beer at the feet of the deceased.
"We help loved ones as much as patients," says Nathalie Savard, director of care.
At the Victor-Gadbois house, the days follow each other but they are not alike.
Alongside a 93-year-old man savouring his last family gathering in the courtyard, tucked in his pillows while drinking in his honor, a 36-year-old man tragically dies, surrounded by his parents, his wife and his two young children, after trying everything to survive.
“For the past six months, there have always been three to five beds occupied by cancer patients under the age of 45,” Dr. Christiane Martel said.
53% of patients who are admitted to the Victor-Gadbois home arrive from their home, 47% come from the hospital.
Access to Palliative Care
It is said that 77% of Canadians simply do not have access to palliative care, that is, care designed to alleviate suffering when a patient has reached the terminal stage of life, whether at home, in a hospital or in a nursing home.
And several organizations, such as Maison Victor-Gadbois and the Société de société de société palliative <0xC3><0xA0> domicile du Grand Montréal, specialize more or less exclusively in the care offered to cancer patients.
It is precisely this great deficiency in Quebec health care that makes many doctors specializing in palliative care fear the adoption of a law governing euthanasia and assisted suicide.
Since October, a manifesto, signed by palliative care leaders including Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe, has been circulating to demonstrate their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, Quebec's health system is not performing well enough to ensure that everyone will be entitled to quality palliative care before euthanasia is accepted.
Recently, she says, I saw a patient spend 14 days in the emergency room, in great pain, without the necessary to relieve her.
I'm afraid patients only ask to die because they don't get the proper care.
And at the same time, several oncologists are working hard on their patients until the last day, despite the worst prognosis.
Helene Richard’s survival expectations were already minimal when she gave up trying chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was stopping treatment, she said she regretted that I stopped fighting, she said.
She told me I was finished!
Not almighty care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who ask to die thank caregivers for not having granted their request after they were relieved of their pain by a palliative care team.
But it must be said that palliative care is not absolutely all-powerful in the treatment of pain.
According to Elsie Monereau, director of palliative care at the Greater Montreal Home Palliative Care Society, patients are said to be refractory to pain treatments in 8% of cases.
At the very end of life, doctors often resort to palliative sedation, which is to put the patient to sleep until the moment of death, either sporadically or permanently.
We can no longer pretend not to hear that part of suffering.
Increasingly, the unrelieved patient will have the opportunity to have this palliative sedation.
The sick who are not relieved always say the same sentence: "I want to die."
But that doesn’t necessarily mean “I want you to euthanize me,” it means “I want to be relieved.”
