With Bitcoin, pay and sell without banks
Quite the opposite of current monetary exchanges, based on central banks, identified transactions and processing fees between stakeholders.
Moreover, as often in these technologies, a political vision is palpable: the belief that the current monetary system, made up of banking monopolies, leads to financial crises.
In fact, Bitcoin, invented by Satoshi Nakamoto (a pseudonym), is both a virtual currency (but convertible into dollars, euros ...) and a secure exchange protocol in the manner of BitTorrent, which allows the exchange of files peer to peer.
Approximately 200,000 transactions have already been recorded through 15,000 computers on the network.
A few thousand websites accept bitcoins as donations or as a means of payment.
The price of bitcoin, after reaching a peak of 30 dollars (23 euros) in June 2011, fell to 2 dollars, five months later, before returning today around ten dollars (the prices are listed on the site bitcoincharts.com).
Nothing very impressive, compared to world trade in real currency or financial products.
Yet, the European Central Bank (ECB) took an interest in this in a report on virtual currencies published in October.
She describes bitcoin as “the most successful virtual currency”, “in competition with the dollar or the euro” and “similar to conventional currencies”.
Bitcoin differs from other types of virtual currency such as “credits”, used to progress in a video game that you win by playing or can buy (and sometimes exchange in return).
The social network Facebook has also developed this kind of system.
But, each time, a central authority controls and processes the exchanges.
With Bitcoin, all nodes in the network are both bookkeepers, auditors, money issuers, and buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Every transaction between two users is actually made between two email addresses in the manner of an e-mail.
Except that a user can choose a different address for each payment, thus ensuring anonymity.
A set of information related to this transaction is electronically signed by a dual-key encryption system.
The network can thus verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the content of the file, it is also possible to ensure that the exchanged bitcoins exist in the public ledger, distributed throughout the network.
The key step is to write this new transaction in this book.
It involves solving a mathematical challenge to computers, the winner of which, as a kind of provisional central banker, will have the privilege of adding this additional line.
This is a file hashing phase, i.e. the transformation of a large file into a shorter and unique digital footprint.
Computers "take" the new transaction and add a number to it before they "hack" the whole thing.
The goal is to find the number that gives a particular footprint (many zeros at the beginning).
Once this number is found, the other nodes easily verify that it is the right one.
The transaction is then indestructibly linked to the chain of all other transactions; any change would change the footprint.
If, to defraud, a user wanted to pay twice with the same money very quickly (less than ten minutes), only one of the two transactions would be validated by the network - the other remaining orphan because the two have different fingerprints.
The computer that solved the challenge wins 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, this reward is divided by two regularly, probably before the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divisible up to one hundred millionth, which leaves room...
The difficulty of the challenge is also met with each increase in computing power.
Network life has already had its ups and downs.
Websites providing services for Bitcoin have been attacked and bitcoins in stolen deposits.
“The flaw used is not about the protocol itself,” says Pierre Noizat, who just launched Paymium, a real-money payment company using the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also mentions the possibilities of money laundering through this anonymous service.
But cash also has this flaw.
Big players like Wikipedia refuse donations of this nature.
Others, like the WordPress blogging platform, accept them.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron, of the Weizmann Institute in Israel, analyzed the ledger and showed that nearly 80% of bitcoins do not circulate.
In November, "giant sales" were launched.
“Thirty thousand dollars have been exchanged,” says Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul, which converts bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, also author of an educational book on this currency, believes a lot in the potential of this technology as a network of transactions.
Its system, Paytunia, is equivalent to a credit card (in real currency) or a contactless mobile payment, but it uses Bitcoin to validate transactions, which thus return cheaper.
The wearer also manages their identity and can therefore be anonymous.
The system is easy to implement for merchants, who do not need to install new terminals or software.
All they have to do is communicate an address that a phone can "photograph and recognize," says Pierre Noizat, who claims to have thousands of users.
There is a general movement to challenge hierarchical systems for more horizontal systems.
“It will take time for Bitcoin to prevail, but 2013 could be a turning point,” he predicts.
The ECB, in its report, also plans to reassess the various risks, now considered high, in case of success of this currency.
We left from Afghanistan.
And then what?
The French troops left their area of responsibility in Afghanistan (Kapisa and Surobi).
NATO and the US are expected to follow by the end of 2014.
It is time for the Afghan army to take back its territory and for the Afghans to choose their future, without expecting anything from us.
It is above all the Afghan peasants that we have punished by considering them as terrorists.
And ourselves, with our 88 soldiers killed, and the wounded, the maimed.
The Taliban are made up of foreign extremists, former chiefs of refugees in Pakistan, but often peasants who refuse the foreign armed presence, as in the days of the Soviets.
They want to defend their traditions, ancient and archaic, even if they have been joined by jihadists, Pakistanis, Arabs, Uzbeks, Tajiks.
Tolerated, sometimes aided by local insurgents, these will no longer be so when Westerners become more discreet.
The departure of the French troops from the Nijrab base, which I observed from the hills planted with almond trees thanks to French credits, was in order.
The convoys of trucks and armored vehicles reached Kabul without being attacked, overflew by helicopters.
There will be no Taliban onslaught on Kabul by the end of 2014.
Circumstances have changed since their irresistible advance from 1994 to 1996.
Kabul was then empty, the country in fire and blood as a result of the struggles between different factions.
Their takeover of the country was then perceived as a kind of liberation, a return to security.
The Afghan women have paid the price for the obscurantism of these farmers who were overtaken by the Al-Qaeda organization, but their situation has not improved nowadays.
Former mujahideen, the Afghan government and the current Taliban are joining in the desire to keep women in an inferior position.
The main notables of the anti-Soviet war returned to power in 2001.
They have turned into businessmen, seizing government land to resell as building land to refugees from Iran and Pakistan, benefiting from huge U.S. subcontracting contracts.
Most of them did not fight on their own; most of them did not fight on their own.
People, as I have heard in the countryside, aspire to a government that is not made up of thieves.
Many young people want to leave, as will those who have profited from American largesse: the flight of capital is considerable.
Young people are tired of war and its ideologies.
They have been around the modern world during their exiles in Iran or Pakistan, they have appreciated the advantages.
About 65% of the population is under 25 years of age; Kabul now has 5 million inhabitants, one fifth of the total population.
In the cities, government schools are full of girls as well as boys.
It will be necessary to provide work for these young people who will no longer want to return to the obscurantism of the old parties or the corruption of certain leaders.
All, including the armed opponents, are fond of mobile phones; television, and its Turkish soap operas that present a modern world, is followed everywhere.
The army is now present.
Will the authorities who will order it be considered legitimate?
Former commanders of the anti-Soviet struggle are already preoccupied with reconstituting provincial militias, which will escape central power.
Afghanistan, a country of mountains, with strong local identities, should be able to benefit from a certain decentralization, like Western nations, but the United States wanted to transform it into a centralized state, with strong presidential power, removing the post of Prime Minister that existed since the 1964 Constitution.
President Karzai does not want foreign controls, especially on the occasion of the elections scheduled for April 2014.
But his country has been dependent on foreign aid since the 1950s and well before that.
No industry has been restarted, no dams are in place, no major irrigation systems are being repaired.
Everything is imported; nothing is produced except fruit and vegetables.
Priority is given to private initiative.
In a country ruined by thirty years of war, government control over infrastructure would have been necessary.
It has been rumored that Afghanistan has immense mineral wealth.
This only added to the feeling that Westerners were only there to seize it.
Without energy to process the iron ore or copper on site, or means of transport to export it through the mountains, there is no mining.
The Chinese have already almost left the Mes Aynak copper mine, leaving international archaeologists (financed by the World Bank) to search the huge Buddhist site and remain the province’s largest employers.
Afghanistan and Pakistan, on which imports and exports largely depend, will one day have to restore normal relations.
The departure of the French combat troops ended on 20 November.
The new cooperation treaty provides for the continuation of traditional aids: high school for girls, boys, department of French at the university, French Institute, cooperation in the military, legal, medical and agricultural fields, support to the Archaeological Delegation.
Since 2009, in an attempt to "win hearts and minds" and to carry out the impossible task of coinciding aid and offensive actions, a service of "civil-military actions" of the Ministry of Defense (Cimic), suppressed in 2012, has carried out, and carried out by a small French NGO, many works of collective interest and agricultural rehabilitation actions in dozens of mountain villages.
These works, greedy in local labor, could help to contain the insurgency: irrigation, wells, drinking water, reforestation, fruit trees, soil protection and increase of arable land.
What will we leave as a memory, after two billion euros of military spending?
A much smaller budget would help to improve the harsh local living conditions in these valleys, which are often more than 2,000 metres above sea level.
The embassy received dozens of written requests for small agricultural achievements from local communities in Kapisa province.
In order for them to free themselves from the insurgency carried out by foreign groups, which I have been told by the farmers to wish for, it would be necessary to maintain in their favour a small, well-controlled civilian aid which affects them directly.
A Forceps Constitution in Egypt
This is a new poker move from President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt remains more divided than ever around the constitutional declaration, which provisionally grants it full powers, it has decided to play its game.
Taking everyone for granted, he announced on Wednesday that the Constituent Assembly would vote on its final text the next day.
Just a week ago, the Head of State gave this House two more months to complete its work.
For almost two years now, Egypt has been relying on a provisional text, which has been amended several times, which weakens institutional stability and leads to legal entanglements.
This new initiative has only increased the fracture in the country.
For his opponents, the President perseveres in his "autocratic delusion", continuing to "betray his word" and "tramp the law".
On the side of its supporters, it is assured that it is a way to end the institutional and political crisis as soon as possible, by accelerating the transition process.
A referendum should be held within 15 days.
A very short period of time that forces the Brothers to give up their project to explain the text, article by article, to the Egyptians.
For the President, it is also a way to regain popular and democratic legitimacy while the protest rages throughout the country.
Mohammed Morsi seems convinced that Egyptians will vote for him, as he said in an interview with the American weekly Time.
Especially since this recourse to a hasty vote is due to the ultimatum to the Egyptian people: "Either you vote for my text, or I keep the full powers", these supposedly end after the adoption of the Constitution.
It was in a strange atmosphere that 85 members of this Constituent Assembly, overwhelmingly Islamist, voted on the text yesterday.
Most of the Liberals missed the call.
In mid-November, shortly before the constitutional declaration, they had slammed the door, feeling that they had not been able to assert their views.
Representatives of human rights, religious minorities and civil society had done the same.
In order for the necessary quorum to be reached, 11 people, replacement members, were added in haste yesterday morning.
Some are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
Unsurprisingly, it is most often unanimously that the articles were voted on.
Commentators have also been amused by the fact that one of the only discrepancies of the day was expressed around... the hour of prayer, some members of the committee believing that the clock of the constituent was badly set.
The text, which was still being voted on last night, contains 234 articles.
Finally, Article 2 remains identical to that of the 1971 Constitution, stipulating that "the principles of sharia are the main source of law."
Salafist parties, for whom the establishment of Islamic law is a major demand, hoped to be able to replace “the principles” with “the rules”, which would have allowed for stricter enforcement.
For the Islamists, the fact that this article has not been amended is a pledge of their good will and respect for the other components of Egyptian society.
“Hypocrisy,” the Liberals reply, seeing it as nothing more than a communication stunt.
For according to them, the Islamization of the Constitution is done through other articles.
These include article 220, which gives Al-Azhar University an advisory role, in particular with regard to verifying the conformity of laws with Sharia law.
According to Egypt specialist Sophie Pommier, this is worrying because "the people called to vote are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
We can see the beginnings of a theocracy.”
The Liberals' fears are further fuelled by the fact that the next rector of this university should be much less moderate than the current one.
"At the moment, there is no concrete religious involvement.
With this Constitution, we remain within the framework of the civil state.
Most of the jurists who have worked on this text are not ulemas but academics, for some trained in the French system," tempers Alexis Blouet, who is preparing a thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
But he acknowledges "there may be ambiguity around Article 220, because the terms used borrow from religious vocabulary.
It refers to "fiqh" in particular [Islamic jurisprudence, ed.].
And the question may arise in the future as to the extent to which civilian judges are competent to rule on it.”
Beyond its religious aspect, the text voted yesterday is highly criticized because of the extensive powers it grants to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood argues that these are significantly reduced compared to what they were under the old regime.
Another contentious point: the powers conferred on the army.
In accordance with the wishes of the military, the review of the defence budget will not be submitted to Parliament, but to a National Defence Council.
Nor will trials of civilians in military courts, as requested by human rights groups, be prohibited.
The latter also express their concerns about the text, which they consider to be liberticidal.
The crime of blasphemy is maintained and insult is now prohibited, which could have serious consequences on freedom of expression, especially of the press.
In addition, no article echoes the protection of women, said Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
According to her, the only positive point was the prohibition of torture under article 36.
The word did not appear in the previous Constitution.
While the Egyptian president was scheduled to speak last night on television, protests are planned this afternoon.
The president’s supporters will march on Saturday.
In Israel, holy places, the Center of the World and a sea of brine await Ukrainian tourists
The Promised Land brings together the grandeur of biblical truths, modern comforts, and wild nature.
Argumenty i Fakty has selected five great reasons to visit Israel.
Go and adore the holy places
An unmissable visit: the banks of the Jordan, where Jesus was baptized.
It is said that anyone who enters these "baptismal funds" will be touched by Divine Grace.
As for Galilee, it is the land of the miracles of Jesus: where the water was changed into wine, where Jesus walked on the water, where he calmed the storm or where the fishing was miraculous.
It is in this precise place that Jesus appeared before his disciples after the Resurrection.
But where you will find the most holy places is in Jerusalem.
Believers walk the Rue de la Souffrance or the Way of the Cross (Latin: Via Dolorosa).
This path begins near the fortress Antonia (the Praetorium), where the trial was held, then leads through the streets of the old town to the Church of the Holy Sepulchre on Golgotha, to the place of the Crucifixion, then to that of the Stone of Anointing and the tomb.
Here is the Christian center of the world, symbol of the salvation of humanity.
According to Christian legend, the monastery of the Cross is erected on the spot where grew the tree used to make the cross on which Jesus was crucified.
Jerusalem is also home to the most sacred place of the Jews: the Western Wall which constitutes the rest of a temple destroyed by the Romans in 70 BC.
According to tradition, people of different faiths leave small words accompanied by prayers that are then answered.
Travel in height
Visit the ruins of the Masada fortress, an ancient refuge against enemies built by Herod the Great in 25 BC for his family.
These ruins are located on the steep rocks of a mountain 450 m above sea level.
Only mountaineers can get there on their own.
For the others, a cable car takes them to this summit full of history.
In the north of the country, between 1,600 and 2,040 m above sea level, is the Mont Hermont ski resort, which welcomes many tourists in winter.
A shuttle can take you there from the foot of the mountain.
The ski slopes are a total of 45 km long.
The old belief is that pagan gods once inhabited the top of the mountain.
Visit unique museums
The country is home to nearly 300 museums.
It is impossible to visit them all in one stay.
Here are the five most interesting that are really worth the detour.
First: the Israel Museum located near the Knesset (parliament).
It houses the very ancient Qumran manuscripts, or Dead Sea Scrolls, discovered in the Judean Desert caves, as well as nearly 500 miles of archaeological and anthropological objects.
See also: Tel Aviv Museum of Art.
The paintings of the Impressionists and Expressionists Monet, Pissarro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall and Picasso are mainly exhibited here.
In Acre, the Hammam Al-Basha awaits you with its Turkish baths composed of casts of visitors and supervisors of the time.
Once in Caesarea, enter the unique private Ralli Museum where you can admire Rodin’s sculptures.
There are no guides or souvenir shops.
Admission is free and donations are prohibited.
The fifth museum is the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem Memorial, located in Tel Aviv, which revisits the most dramatic historical pages in history.
The most tragic part is the children’s memorial, built in memory of the 1.5 million children exterminated in concentration camps and gas chambers.
You enter and enter in total darkness.
Stars are twinkling.
Then you hear the names of the Jewish children and the names of the countries in which they died.
Ukraine is also mentioned.
Health and well-being
The three major seaside resorts of Israel are located on the shores of the Mediterranean Sea, the Red Sea and the Dead Sea.
Each of them offers swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums and giant aquariums.
Note: you can swim in the Red Sea even in winter, because the water temperature does not drop below 21°C while the air can reach 23°C.
The Dead Sea is even hotter and you can swim in it all year round.
By the way, this is the most unique sea in the world: it occupies the lowest point on Earth, 417 m below sea level.
The azure-colored water contains brine and very easily retains bathers, even those who do not know how to swim.
The landscapes that surround it are of surreal beauty.
We come there to carry out a treatment based on salt water, silt, healing mud and to cure various diseases such as dermatitis, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes but also to simply relax.
Discover the secrets of Antiquity
They are guarded by Tel Aviv’s Old City, Jaffa, on the edge of the Mediterranean Sea.
It is crossed by the famous Via Maris that connects Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia.
The city is mentioned in Greek and Egyptian legends of antiquity.
According to legend, it is here that Noah built his ark and that Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda, with whom he lived a long and happy life here.
Tourists especially like to stroll through the narrow alleys that are named after the signs of the zodiac.
It is said that if you touch the walls of the street corresponding to "your" sign, fate will smile at you.
In Jaffa you can meet newlyweds who have come to take pictures from all over Israel and even from other countries.
In Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can stroll through the Roman theater, "conquer" the Crusader fortress.
Under the Roman Empire, Caesarea was the main city of Judea and the residence of Roman prosecutors, including Pontius Pilate.
The carefully restored theatre is now used for evening concerts and opera performances.
Note to tourists
If you go to Israel, don’t worry about your English: about 30% of the population speaks Russian.
For your trip, it is better to prefer dollars to euros, as they are easily exchangeable in shekels (today 1 dollar is equivalent to 3.8 shekels).
In terms of urban transport, these are mainly buses, but Jerusalem is equipped with a fast tram and Haifa has the only metro line in the country, consisting of six stations and able to connect the lower and upper parts of the city.
It is almost an underground funicular.
The journey in all types of public transport costs 6 shekels and allows you to make changes for 1h30.
In Israel, the Jewish tradition is to celebrate the Sabbath on Saturday.
From Friday evening until sunset on Saturday, markets, shops and public transport cease to operate.
And the work week begins on Sunday morning.
Many cafes, restaurants, and hotels serve only kosher food, which excludes pork, seafood, scaleless fish, and dishes consisting of both milk and meat.
It offers a multitude of lamb and beef dishes, soups and desserts based on coconut milk but also hummus, traditional Jewish dough, different sauces, ground chickpea balls, falafels, fruits and vegetables.
There are no stray dogs on the streets of Israeli cities.
On the other hand, there are many well-fed cats that walk the haughty air.
They can be seen sleeping on the roofs of parked cars at night.
These felines love passing places and do not refuse to be enjoyed.
Renting a car varies depending on the brand from $37 for 24h (Hyundai Getz) to $188 (Audi A6, Volvo S80).
Insurance costs $15 a day.
Renting a bike will cost you 15 shekels a day.
Admission to the museum costs an average of 30 shekels.
The Language of Numbers
Three million tourists from all over the world visited Israel in 2012.
These were mostly people who came to travel and rest from the United States, Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England and Ukraine.
118.8 miles of Ukrainian tourists visited the Promised Land from January to October 2012, 51% more than in 2010, before the cancellation of visas on February 9, 2011.
"Who has language, in Moscow goes": migrants save money to learn the language
As MPs and human rights activists debate what the law on compulsory language testing will bring, fraudsters selling "fake" certificates have already made an appearance in the country
Every year, 13 million migrant workers come to Moscow, St. Petersburg and other Russian cities.
Most of them are citizens of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal: to earn money to help their families stay at home.
Since December 1st, a law has come into force stipulating that every migrant worker will have to pass a Russian exam.
For the time being, this rule applies only to those intending to work in the services, housing, personal services and retail sectors.
However, over time, promises the Federal Migration Service, tests will become mandatory for all immigrants.
In addition, it will be necessary to validate the knowledge of the language, but also that of the History of Russia and the foundations of law.
It will be necessary to validate your language skills in Russian to obtain and renew your work permit.
Only nationals of countries where Russian has official language status are exempt.
Persons who obtained educational certificates or diplomas before the fall of the USSR in 1991 are also not covered by this law.
Benefit, negative attitude and protection of rights
The network of examination centers will be under the aegis of the Pushkin Institute of Russian Language, the University of Friendship of Peoples, Moscow State University, St. Petersburg State University and other Russian higher education institutions.
Immigrants will be able to take the exams in all the cities of the country: more than 160 centers have already been opened throughout the territory.
This initiative to introduce examinations was supported by the deputies of the State Duma and the Federal Migration Service.
But, before the law comes into force, human rights defenders have already repeatedly asked the question in the press: what will it give?
What will the obligation to know Russian change for Russians and immigrants?
First of all, respond representatives of the migration service, it will reduce the number of people suffering "slavery at work".
Many are talking about defending the rights of migrant workers, says Victor Sebelev, director of the Russian Federal Migration Service’s office in Tajikistan.
The protection of rights must begin before their departure.
Only an organized system of selection will solve 90% of the problems of foreign workers.
Problems arise for migrants without a profession, without training, who do not know the language and who do not have medical certificates.
Without understanding the language, Sebelev certifies, the future migrant is destined to meet dishonest people who, under the pretext of helping him, will provide him with a "trip" to an overcrowded house where he and dozens of his fellows will torment themselves for months without food and without papers and will have to work between 12 and 14 hours a day.
We receive many complaints from our migrants.
"They are promised one thing, and when they arrive, they are deceived, they take their passports, and they do not receive the expected salary," confirms the Head of the Directorate of Migration Services for Labour of the Migration Service of Tajikistan, Tolib Sharipov.
Don't argue with me, officer!
However, many citizens of the Central Asian republics who want to come to Russia to earn money are confident that they not only do not know the language of the country where they want to go, but also that they write with difficulty in their own language.
It is not their fault, of course, but their misfortune: few Turkmen, Uzbeks, Tajiks can afford even a fair primary education.
Indeed, their families do not even have enough to feed their children without talking about dressing them properly and equipping them for school.
As soon as they reach adolescence, these young people leave to earn money as soon as the opportunity presents itself.
It’s hard when you don’t know the language, they confide.
"You feel diminished and diminished."
However, human rights defenders note an important aspect of the language law.
The exams will be intended only for migrants who have legal status.
Without status, there will be no formal examination or work afterwards.
Yet most migrant workers continue to live in Russia illegally.
"Welcome or welcome to enter"
Many immigrants explain that it is not so easy to obtain official status in Russia.
The reason? Administrative barriers and always these language difficulties.
In addition, legalization costs money: between 12 and 16 rubles.
And then one can get a fake registration quickly for only 1,500 rubles.
The Russian police know that we have false documents, that we do not have a record, hence the cases of extortion.
“They are asking us for 100, 200 rubles, enough to buy cigarettes, tea,” Umed Khoushkadamov, a Tajikistani national, told reporters.
“Make it quick, don’t skimp, and buy yourself a beautiful work of art.”
From the first day of the entry into force of the Language Act, it was discovered that the registration papers of migrants were not the only ones to be false.
Several fake language test certificates have already been confiscated by employees of the Federal Migration Service.
Falsified papers come out of an ordinary color printer.
Of course, their new owners did not take them for nothing: every migrant who hoped to make the examinations easier had to pay seven thousand rubles for this document.
It is two and a half times more expensive than the official procedure: it will cost the migrant worker three thousand rubles.
Officials and human rights advocates agree that the short-term goal is to protect the system from corruption so that it is impossible to simply buy these "paper bits".
The authorities can give migrant workers who have not been able to pass the examination on the first try time to take language courses.
In addition, immigrants who do not know Russian will be offered work in areas that do not involve actively communicating with people.
The Ministry of the Interior does not deal with the arms market
The share of crimes involving legal weapons is very low
The Russian Ministry of the Interior proposes to toughen the law against civilian weapon bearers.
This is the reaction of the authorities in the face of recent incidents: whether it is the shootings carried out at weddings or the massacre organized by the Moscow lawyer Dmitry Vinogradov, which left seven dead.
Police want to ban the use of rubber bullets in public places and raise the legal age for a gun licence from 18 to 21.
The idea was supported by the head of the Duma committee for security and anti-corruption, Irina Yarovaya, who promised that amendments to the arms law would be introduced in the State Duma soon.
Not everyone is happy to see that the Russian authorities are trying to solve the problem by "tightening the screw".
An open letter appeared on the Net in which its authors, representatives of various shooting centers, demand to abandon "this senseless hardening".
The percentage of crimes committed with a registered weapon is minimal, Vasiliy Lesnikov, a lawyer and crime specialist for the BBC, told the Russian service.
According to statistics from the Ministry of the Interior, over a six-month period in 2012, 142 crimes were committed with a firearm registered in the police services while 1,168 thousand crimes were recorded over the same period.
The authors of the open letter are confident that strengthening civilian gun laws will not prevent criminals from sourcing from the black market.
According to them, any weapon can be found in Moscow today for a reasonable price.
However, the Ministry of the Interior says it controls the spread of illegal weapons.
Suppliers: from factory to officer
The black market in arms is provided through several channels.
There are five main canals, says Victor Baranets, a retired colonel who served in the Ministry of Education and Headquarters for 10 years.
Screenshot from a site taking gun orders
The first is "military trace", that is, weapons that were stolen during military operations in the Caucasus.
“These weapons were stolen by Russian officers, but also by Caucasians,” Baranets said.
The second type of black market weapons are those stolen by criminals from law enforcement.
Baranets explains that these are both weapons stolen from police stocks and those stolen directly from law enforcement officials.
Illegal pistols go on sale from military warehouses.
Many of them have often suffered explosions.
“Attested versions indicate that some fires were deliberately set to hide the deficit,” the former military official said.
For Baranets, the arms manufacturers have something to do with it.
“We see private arms factories that do not compete with the competition in the international market and sell weapons on the black market, especially in Moscow,” says an expert.
One of the other sources of the black market is smuggling.
A significant proportion of pistols and submachine guns come from poor countries, such as Kyrgyzstan.
“There is a local production, sometimes artisanal, a mafia has formed and organizes the supply,” adds the former military.
Where did the weapons come from?
Experts assessed the approximate share of each source of illegal weapons on the black market.
A report on the issue was established in 2011 by the Centre for Problem Analysis and Study of Public Administration.
Specialists analysed reports from the Ministry of the Interior and Rosstat, criminal records and public data from weapons portals.
The vast majority of illegal weapons, the researchers explain, come from the military and law enforcement.
Half of the weapons on the black market ended up there "due to the fault of employees whose work is related to weapons," the report said.
According to the researchers, 17% of the weapons come from places of military conflict, 14% are stolen at the time of manufacture and 5% are from “clandestine excavations”.
An armoury salesman and consultant who asked to remain anonymous says that for a long time no one has bought the weapons found by these clandestine search specialists; they are too old.
Most often, according to him, sellers will look for the new goods in military warehouses.
The person buys through a sign a unit, for example a TT gun.
It is delivered to him by passing the goods through a wire mesh.
“He transports it to the city and resells it for €900 per unit with two chargers,” he says.
“It is true that the police are aware of all the cases, so when crimes are about to be solved, they make a control purchase from the illegal arms dealers,” the seller adds.
"Like in a luxury boutique"
The seller and the buyer are usually found through knowledge.
I consulted websites, blogs, until a guy showed up and offered to come to Begovaya station where someone would take me to a "corner" to haggle.
The price of the gun, they gave it to me on the spot
Victor Baranets as military observer
To find a gun, I need to know someone who has a contact, explains the seller. I know someone, but I do not trust him.
There are sellers in the markets, but there must also come saying for example "On behalf of such a person, who asked me to convey that his daughter has lost a tooth".
Now I even buy a pair of American fists with the help of someone I trust.
He only gives them to me because he knows I won't give them to him.
Young children look for weapons in different ways.
Former military officer Victor Baranets tried his hand as a buyer of illegal weapons in the mid-1990s when he was preparing to publish an article on the subject.
The patterns, he said, have not changed.
He was given a photo album in which there was "everything we want".
