"At the moment, we can only averagely fool the brain"
Lately, fans of new technologies have become accustomed to perceiving augmented reality through special glasses.
Initially, it was Google that unveiled this summer its current model at its annual conference and in November we learned that Microsoft had applied for the patent.
However, it is clear from the interview with the director of the group of interactive 3D technologies of the Microsoft laboratory in Cambridge, Shahram Izadi, that for the scientists of this company, the glasses are already ancient history.
They are tempted by the prospect of manipulating virtual objects in the air with their bare hands, by creating open virtual spaces.
- Could you tell us in a few words what your research group is doing?
- We are working on the interaction between man and machine and at the same time we are trying to expand the boundaries of this interaction.
Humanity as a whole has remained for the moment to the pixels on a flat screen and sometimes to the touch.
We want to look 5 to 10 years ahead of us and guess at the radical changes that will occur with this interaction.
For example, the Xbox console and Kinect sensors are a step forward, and almost no Xbox is sold today without Kinect because everyone is interested in gesture control.
- What does the future hold?
- Although the Kinect rendered the physical interaction, a lot of things happen on a flat screen, sometimes in 3D.
The information capture has been improved (the system receives more data), but the performance, for now, not really.
We’re trying to change that and we’re working on truly 3D imaging systems that run on different technologies, including projection technologies.
We have to take the computer world out into our own, into the physical world, make it more tactile.
For this, however, it is necessary to identify not only the user, but also the space that surrounds him.
Thus, we will be able to complete the real world with virtual objects in a more practical form.
And for starters, let’s get rid of those stupid virtual reality headsets!
- What do you think of voice control?
It’s appreciated, but isn’t it overrated?
It cannot be called a panacea: the question of confidentiality arises because one does not always want to inform others of one's actions or intentions.
In fact, every type of interaction with the computer is good, but each in its niche.
For example, to order the devices in public places, we had a project for which we thought of gestures, not broad gestures, but rather discreet, restricted gestures.
The gestures were not captured by the camera of the device, but by a bracelet worn by the hand that recorded the movements of the bones and muscles.
It is currently large, but it is theoretically possible to reduce it to the size of a watch.
In fact, the future will be marked by the mixed command, for example: gesture + voice.
- What do you mean?
- For example, how would you ask me to pass you this can?
You would do it with words and gestures.
- I usually just talk.
- Oh, it's gonna be hard to recognize.
- So, you want to force users to adapt based on what the machine may or may not do at any given time?
- Not necessarily, but it is a mutual rapprochement.
I think that very soon we will have to work on the development of new types of sensors that will allow us to better identify human reactions.
These can be for example laser sensors, they produce a fairly good resolution in depth and this is very important.
- If we are interested in your work on Xbox Kinect sensors, what is it that you do not like in modern cameras?
Do they lack resolution, depth, or something else?
- In principle, it is on the current generation that we base our work on 3D recognition.
It would obviously be good to get about 8 megapixels with a speed of 1000 c/s.
But the problem is not the megapixels themselves, but the quality of the matrix and the depth.
Compared to this last point, all current technologies are quite good, it adds work to the algorithm designers.
It is necessary to keep in mind the resolution along the axes X and Y, but also Z.
Speed also matters a lot, the number of frames per second.
Human movements are quite dynamic, and 30 c/s is really not enough, especially for gestures.
Steven Bathiche, from our laboratory in Redmond, gave the sensor touch a regular processing delay of between 1 and 100 <0xCE><0xBC>s, with the current sensors being closer to the second value (60-100).
Not everyone understands how much this influences the interaction of man and machine.
I would need a device of this type in my work, but not requiring touch, to have more frames per second.
Shouldn’t the number of cameras be increased?
The Kinect now has three cameras, one of which is actually an infrared transmitter and the second, a reflected signal receiver.
And the third camera is actually a regular visible field sensor.
It is not used to define the depth of the object.
Many cameras can solve this problem.
Or make it worse by increasing the required volume of calculations.
It would be interesting to create a flexible product similar to the Kinect, play with the curve of the cameras and see how it could help define the locations.
As far as I can remember, Microsoft, unlike Google, did not present its glasses to the public.
Don’t you think that from a point of view of the daily use of augmented reality technologies, glasses are one of the platforms with the most perspectives?
- Of course, walking around all the time with a smartphone with your hands up is not practical but here's what I think: the best option would be a "transient" augmented reality that would allow you from a cloud platform to switch from glasses to the smartphone.
Glasses are a very personal device and that's what makes them strong (the personal elements are those that you are the only one to see) and at the same time their weakness: augmented reality from glasses will not allow you to work on virtual objects in collaboration with other people.
- Let's imagine for a moment that the manipulation of virtual holographic objects in the air is no longer accessible only to Tony Stark in Iron Man but also to the mere mortal.
There is a problem on which opponents of this idea point the finger: there is no tactile sensation!
The hands feel nothing.
What responses is your group preparing for this challenge?
- In my classes, I often say that augmented reality is the seventh breakthrough in the interaction between man and machine.
I think the eighth could very well be the addition of tactile sensations.
For the moment, one of the interesting techniques is the use of the second hand to serve as an image support.
It perfectly records the pressures!
But there are also technologies that are really intended to attribute palpability to these "images in the air": for example the interference of several ultrasound rays directed to a precise point where the finger is located and which gives you the sensation, for the moment still weak, of a breath of air on the tips of the fingers.
There are also bracelets worn on the wrists that affect the nerve endings of the fingers, they are also a working axis with perspectives.
- And you tried to trick the brain?
Make him believe that he feels what he should normally feel the moment he sees something?
- That's a good idea, we haven't tried it yet.
There’s one more task down there that will take a long time to work on: how to make someone who’s physically in a very small space think they’re walking in an almost infinite open space – we’re working on the concepts of treadmills (nothing to do with those found in fitness clubs), mobile platforms and also giant balls.
At the moment, we can only averagely fool the brain, there are still many years of work left.
This is what makes the work on virtual reality so interesting for the researcher: many things are still in the absolute state of fertilization.
