Giving Birth in Space
The Earth is in danger.
Global warming or collision with a deadly asteroid.
Caravans of space shuttles with Earthlings on board go in search of a rescue planet.
To save humanity, a big question arises: how to continue to make our species live in weightlessness or on a rescue planet?
I don't think there's much of a choice.
There are actually two real planets that can be conquered, if only by hypothesis.
"This is Venus and Mars," says Vladimir Sourdine, a researcher at the P.K. Chternberg State Astronomical Institute (GAICh).
If conditions on Mars are more suitable for life, the temperature on the surface of Venus is 500 degrees Fahrenheit.
We can only live there at very high altitude or in the orbit of Venus... in space.
We began to focus on the issues of reproduction in space by focusing on the flora.
Half a century ago, experiments were conducted on plants.
Four generations of peas grown in orbit did not differ in any way from terrestrial varieties.
Then we put into orbit insects, small reproductive Drosophila flies.
In 1979, quail eggs were sent into space to see how a weightless embryo developed.
At the exit, a completely normal chick is obtained.
Then the problems begin.
"The problem is that the chick has to find support, it has to get on its legs and start moving," says the director of the laboratory of the Institute of Medical-Biological Problems of the Russian Academy of Sciences (IMBP) Vladimir Sychev.
Finding no support, the chicks agitated in a disordered manner.
And after 10 hours, the newborns saw their instincts completely atrophied.
The chicks did not react to light or sound.
Unfortunately, they would simply die after four days.
“We widened their eyes twice, and then we gave up, because it is simply impossible to work with them there,” says Vladimir Sychev, noting the failure of the experiment with chicks in space.
The last biological "miniature ark" with animals was sent into orbit 16 years ago.
The experiments will continue in the spring of 2013.
However, the biosatellite "Bion" will only carry species of the same sex.
There was an experiment with rats sent with their fetuses into space.
In principle, nothing supernatural has been discovered.
"It was still about biosatellites and then it's the only experiment. You have to do this kind of research," notes Vladimir Sychev.
After landing, the space rats gave birth to their offspring.
However, reproductions directly in space are not yet possible.
It's no small matter.
By losing their usual environment, animals are no longer able to carry out their sexual instincts.
Unlike animals, humans are capable of this in principle.
Homo sapiens has abstract thinking, it is able to create a suitable emotional background.
This type of experiment is not conducted for ethical reasons.
Women have been in space for 50 years.
The biggest risk was taken by Tereshkova.
And the female organism is what humanity has most precious.
Our seagull flew away and no one on Earth could tell if it would hold up after a flight into space.
If only she could have given birth to a child after the robbery.
“No one was answering that question,” says Vakhtang Vatchnadze, a rocket and space retiree.
In June 1964, just one year after her flight into space, the first female cosmonaut Valentina Tereshkova gave birth to a baby girl.
The child's father, Andrian Nikolayev was also a cosmonaut.
In 1988, the second female cosmonaut Svetlana Savitskaya, after being twice in orbit and even working in an extra-vehicular environment, gave birth to a son.
However, the risk persists.
We have few, even very few cosmonauts who have had nothing and who give birth to a healthy offspring after long flights.
"And if they are longer, this presents a danger even during flights in orbit," concludes the pilot and cosmonaut, hero of the Soviet Union and hero of Russia, Valeriy Poliakov.
Yet humanity must seek new solutions in biotechnologies, radiation protection and the creation of artificial gravity.
Hydrology laboratory of the Cosmonaut Preparation Center: mandatory step of preparation for flight.
Here, in zero buoyancy, cosmonauts train for extra-vehicular sorties.
Water imitates weightlessness.
If for adults, water is comfortable but yet a foreign environment, for infants, it is their true element.
Small amphibious men seem to confirm it: life on Earth comes from the ocean.
Since the baby evolves about 9 months in the lymphatic fluid of his mother's belly, it is easier for him to get used to water afterwards.
This is in principle logical, because from its birth until its first bath, it happens only 2 weeks.
“It’s very little to forget,” says infant swimming instructor Marina Aksenova.
In a word, if for the child who has just been born weightlessness is a more natural state, the woman needs gravitation, a force of weight.
In weightlessness, the muscles of the belly, pelvis atrophy very quickly, the baby's ability to push is lost.
Okay, well, let's ignore that by relying on birth simulators.
We can of course prepare a birth in a special room, the woman will manage to get it out.
"And then?" asks Valeriy Poliakov to invite reflection on this complex question.
On the other hand, the child also needs artificial gravitation.
If it does not feel the terrestrial attraction, the organism does not form the skeleton or the muscular system.
It is not possible to dress an infant as an adult with a special combination for training.
He will simply be deprived of his vital needs.
"And this experiment that we would consider in this case by imagining the birth of a child in a foreign environment will lead to the return to Earth of a disabled child, completely maladaptive," predicts the Director of the Committee for Bioethics of the Institute of Medical-Biological Problems of the Russian Academy of Sciences, Igor Pestov.
The birth of children in space is still a theory.
However, over time this will become a reality, when Earthlings travel in their shuttles to a distant planet that will become the habitat of their space-born offspring.
