Do you therefore consider the adoption of this law rather as an advantage or as an additional burden for the administration?
I think this legislation is a step in the right direction and I hope that the future will confirm that.
The problem that can arise is that these rules become more stringent and it is not possible to respect them.
Already under the previous regulations, the claimant (e.g. the Regional Council, in the case of the Regional Operational Programmes) required the audited subjects to accept that any breach of the Contracts Act would mean a breach of budgetary discipline.
So is it really useful to make the law tougher in this way?
No, not that way, I think.
The system must exclude those who want to attack the system or abuse it but not punish those who make formal mistakes with no consequence on the decision-making process.
Such a system will put more pressure on the administration.
So what is the solution to get out of it?
Let's look where we're not going.
Recently, the Prime Minister said that the ODS is not going to bother entrepreneurs with controls of the so-called <0xC5><0xA0>varc system - what does that mean?
Is the <0xC5><0xA0>varc system prohibited or allowed?
The law has to be enforced in one way or another, so if it prohibits something, even the head of government can't stop an authority from inspecting and enforcing the law.
He may declare, "We will change the law and authorize it," but he cannot say that we will act as if it were nothing.
The contract law contains relatively strict rules on the formalities to be completed, precisely in order to protect the tender.
But it is also tragic that a bidder is eliminated solely because of formal defects.
The law will never be perfect, but its application must be just and that is, in my opinion, what is lacking in us.
