<0xC5><0xA0>imon Ornest said: “In concert we want to collect positive energy.”
What do you think about the fact that in less than a month it should be the end of the world?
This is just one of those alarming news stories, the kind of traps we like to fall into.
In our group The Tap Tap, we laugh rather and we think that we are the only group able to collect a remnant of positive energy in order to repel or prevent the end of the world.
In addition, in December you are mounting a completely unique project: three concerts against the end of the world.
Can you explain this project in more detail to our readers?
This is a charity that we have been preparing for two years.
We decided to use the marketing potential of the end of the Mayan calendar announced for December 21 at 11:10 am.
The day before, on December 20, three concerts will take place simultaneously, in Prague, Brno and Ostrava.
They will end almost as soon as the Mayan calendar ends on the island of Kiribati, which is in the Pacific Ocean, on a time zone 12 hours ahead of us.
Who came up with that idea?
At first I think it was my idea, then we designed everything with our creator, Honza Augusta.
Apart from the fact that we want to collect enough positive energy to save the world, we also want together, with the public, to reflect on the state of the world that we leave to our children.
On the occasion of the end of the Mayan calendar, we have created a collection of unique items, including shoes, T-shirts, bags, and original keys against the end of the world, by purchasing them online at www.e-tap.cz people can also support us.
The group The Tap Tap with other performers also recorded an anthem against the end of the world which is entitled "End of the world cancelled" (in Czech " Konec sv<0xC4><0x9B>ta zru<0xC5><0xA1>eno ").
It is already very popular on YouTube, will we hear it also during these charity concerts?
Of course, all in the end, finally, if we succeed and the end of the world does not take place...
It will be sung simultaneously by all performers in all three concerts.
The anthems will also come together at some point as part of a unique live Czech television program.
The lyrics of this song were written by Tomá<0xC5><0xA1> Hanák who also plays the lead role of Jesus in the clip, Xindl X also sings in it...
How did you come to cooperate with them?
We collaborate with other personalities of the Czech show-biz, due to the fact that we organize numerous concerts and charitable events...
We strive to involve them intensively in these projects.
It turned out that most of them are interested in such cooperation and that it amuses them.
What are the benefits of these concerts against the end of the world?
To equip the Studeo training center which is accessible to people with reduced mobility and which we are working on within the framework of the Jedli<0xC4><0x8D>ka institute, with the Tap association, and that for six years.
Teachers regularly visit the students of the Jedli<0xC4><0x8D>k<0xC5><0xAF>v Institute and offer them activities that interest and amuse them.
The students themselves do not have the means to go to classes, we try to help them in this way.
As part of the completion of the construction of the Jedli<0xC4><0x8D>ka Institute, we will transfer this project to a new independent building.
Will several bands and performers take to the stage at each of these concerts?
By what criteria do you choose them?
We have tried to develop a program for all generations, including children.
For example, in Prague, Chinaski, Support Lesbians, Illustratosphere with Dan Bárta, The Tap Tap, Marián Bango and Ji<0xC5><0x99><0xC3><0xAD> Such<0xC3><0xBD> will take the stage.
Full details can be found at www.kpks.cz.
Are you also preparing for other “mega events” of this kind in the future?
In May, we will play for the first time in the Prague Spring; there too, we will surely prepare a quality program with interesting guests.
We would also like to play next year at the house of the Czech Republic in New York and personally, once there in the United States, I would like to combine concerts in Washington and Chicago.
Your international projects are minimalist, so far you have played for example in Madrid, Brussels, London and Moscow.
The Tap Tap is a group of people with disabilities.
How do you manage the organization and logistics of your tours?
It’s not so bad that it looks like it at first.
We have five members in an electric chair whose gear must travel in the hold, of course we also carry a lot of luggage and boxes of instruments....
So far everything has more or less always gone well, <0xC4><0x8C>SA and British Airways were always perfectly prepared for us, they surprised me more than once.
Even in Moscow, from where we recently returned, everything went smoothly.
Through your travels abroad, you can compare how these countries differ in terms of accessibility for people with reduced mobility, public attitudes towards people with disabilities and so on.
What have been your experiences so far?
After Madrid, Luxembourg, London and other places where everything works better than at home, we have just witnessed in Moscow that it is all still in an initial phase.
Compared to Prague, Moscow is still very inaccessible to people with disabilities; there, it is not yet common for a person to travel alone in an electric chair in the center of the city.
They do not yet consider it obvious to give priority to a person in a wheelchair in an elevator.
Fortunately, there too, an association was being set up to draw attention to the problems of persons with disabilities.
How do we still have to catch up with the more developed countries?
There are a lot of things we are still late for...
It is important to note that improvements and refinements always depend on the efforts of those involved.
In London and Madrid, it is quite common for people with a heavy disability to move alone in public spaces; they can go to the toilet, to the museum, anywhere...
It is still not very common there that a large number of people with disabilities actively participate in social life, on this point, you, The Tap Tap, are rather at the forefront of progress!
Respect for the public and ease of access are one thing, but the situation will really start to change when we have famous athletes, artists, actors, politicians or lawyers among us.
At the moment, these are only isolated cases of people who have a strong will.
The Tap Tap is currently very popular, let's go back a few years, what prompted you in 1998 to create this group?
I started working as an educator at the Jedli<0xC4><0x8D>ka Institute, where I found myself surrounded by many young people willing to get involved in something.
And since I am a musician myself (I play, among other things, the saxophone), with a colleague, we created a music activity.
And then, with time, as our moderator Lá<0xC4><0x8F>a Angelovi<0xC4><0x8D> says, we lost a little control of the situation (laughs).
Success has only happened in the last few years, if I'm not mistaken?
It's true, connecting with well-known singers and actively working to promote the band has helped us.
We understood that if a work is not visible, it is as if it does not exist in the background.
Thanks to European Union grants, we can, in addition, afford to have quality teachers, equipment, and so on.
Were you aiming to reach such a level with The Tap Tap?
From the beginning, I felt there was potential to change things.
Show business is full of stuff that copies each other.
In a way, it makes sense: everything new is accepted with caution and it lasts a long time.
There are few original projects, and I dare say that Tap Tap is one of them.
The first impression of a person who sees us for the first time is naturally pity, it is natural ...
But pity is totally useless, because people with disabilities are not suffering beings, abandoned by all, whom we must take pity on.
These are people who can live a full life and thrive, provided they have the means to do so of course.
I often say that when people with disabilities achieve something, it is not only a breakthrough for them but for society as a whole.
Isn’t your success also due to the fact that you are a demanding leader, as you are qualified by many people?
If we want to do quality work, we have to be uncompromising in many areas and demand some discipline.
But I think that's perfectly normal.
Some people come to us with a romantic vision and head in the clouds and, when they realize that they have to come to rehearsals twice a week, take preparatory classes and spend a lot of time on the roads for concerts, they quickly lose their enthusiasm.
But it works the same way in every group that wants to work and achieve goals.
The group The Tap Tap currently has twenty members.
How many were there in 1998?
Only one, Lá<0xC4><0x8F>a Angelovi<0xC4><0x8D>.
We're an open group, people come and go, we can't help it.
Our doors are always open to those who want or would like to join us.
