Poland and the cosmos.
Last week, at the meeting of the Ministers of the countries of the European Space Agency, Poland was admitted as the twentieth member of this agency, it is the second member of the former Eastern bloc (the Czech Republic became a full member on 12 November 2008).
Poland had started working closely with ESA in 1994 and in the following years participated in a number of ESA projects.
However, Poland's journey into space began much earlier.
Already before the Second World War, passionate Poles worked on space flights; they did not always meet with understanding.
I would like to mention, for example, the lecture given by A. <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld at the Astronomical Observatory in Warsaw on 6 December 1933, in which he presented ideas drawn from his avant-garde work entitled "Introduction to Astronautics".
The developments of this young engineer (born in 1905) left the listeners cold and years later <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
In 1934, <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld won the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch Prize in France for his book Introduction <0xC3><0xA0> l'astronautique.
The said doctor Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became a great propagator of astronomy and astronautics.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish newspapers and wrote many books devoted to this scientific discipline.
Gadomski became a world-renowned propagator of astronautics, his contribution was notably rewarded by the fact that his name was given to one of the craters on the far side of the Moon.
As early as 1925, a dragisine was built in Poland to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, neither the author nor the details of this project are known.
It is also unclear whether the rocket was to be used to propel or brake the dragisine.
The only known information about this drawing is that of the press at the time.
From 1933, the Polish artillery began to devote itself to rockets.
The research was conducted by the Kom<0xC3><0xB3>rka Techniki Uzbrojenia Institute in collaboration with Professors Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Gustaw Mokrzyckiego.
It appears from the documents retained that this research had reached the stage of testing.
Of course, with the arrival of the German armies, the search was interrupted.
In 1937, the plans of a photoelectric hunting rocket, drawn by the engineer Rohozi<0xC5><0x84>ski, appeared in the specialized press and the following year the book "Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" by an author named Leliwy-Krzywoblocki was published.
These two projects were intended for military use of rocket engines.
Just before the war, all projects for the use of rocket technology were carried out by the Provisional Scientific Advisory Committee ("Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy"), which coordinated all work.
This committee had been created in 1937, but after two years of operation, the beginning of the war put an end to its activities.
After the war, other works devoted to aeronautics were published in the Polish press, thanks to the Polish Astronautical Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
For the first time, a company is mentioned in the November 1954 issue of the newspaper Probl<0xC3><0xA8>me, in which there are four more detailed articles devoted to aeronautics.
In one of these articles, written by Professor M. Subotowicze, it is proposed to create a society dedicated to astronautics.
At that time, artificial satellite projects had already been launched and it was clear that the field of space research had a future.
In early 1956, the Polish Astronautical Society (PTA) made efforts to join the International Astronautical Federation (established in 1951) and by the autumn the PTA became a regular member.
The following year, the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became vice-president of the International Astronautical Federation.
He remained in office until his death in 1959.
From 1956, the PTA made a significant contribution to the successful development of the RM (Rakieta Meteorologiczna) weather rocket, which became the first Polish rocket to conduct scientific research.
The first model, RM-1, was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
This rocket with a range of 1800 meters had a length of 80 cm and weighed just under 5 kg.
Subsequently, an improved version, RM-1A, was built and, in the summer of 1959, flight tests of the two-stage RM-2 rocket began in the Bledov desert.
This rocket had a length of 1.4 meters and probably weighed 11.5 kg.
The next prototype should have been able to carry out concrete scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should have a range of up to 14.5 km and be used to observe the wind at altitude.
But in 1963, all development work was stopped.
The Meteor-1 rocket, developed during the period 1962-1965, succeeded the first RM-type rockets.
This rocket, designed with two stages, had a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three models (named Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed; they were distinguished by the dimensions of the space reserved for scientific tools.
The Meteor-1A rocket had space with a volume of 0.4 liters, while in Meteor-1B this volume was 0.34 liters and in Meteor-1C 0.62 liters.
The maximum range of all these types of craft was 37 km.
In the period 1965 - 1968, the Meteor-2 rockets were developed in the aeronautical institute, the first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was capable of carrying a payload of 10 kg at an altitude of about 60 km.
The Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were later built.
The entry of Poland into COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the creation of a national COSPAR committee two years later should also be mentioned.
As part of the Interkosmos program, Poland also participated in space exploration on artificial Soviet satellites and, in 1978, the pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became, after Vladim<0xC3><0xAD>r Remek, the second non-Soviet cosmonaut of this program.
Repeal of the Public Works Act is not a solution.
Last week, the Constitutional Court repealed the Public Works Act.
This decision has given rise to much public discussion.
It is certainly interesting to look at this issue from a broader point of view.
Liberalised economic systems, both in the EU and in the context of globalisation, are based on the principle of more unregulated economic competition.
This means in practice that the different economic entities as well as the national economic systems are perpetually in conflict with each other.
This results from the principle of freedom of trade and the free (without limits) movement of private capital combined with unbridled financial speculation.
The considerable differences in the price of labour (wages) generate a pressure on prices.
The meaning of this term should be understood as follows: a producer endeavours, through the importation of goods sold cheaply, to resist economic competition by "making" the price of the competitor more expensive, with the aim of removing a greater share of the market and thus increasing his own profits.
On a large scale, this means for most entrepreneurs: either transferring production abroad, or buying cheaply, or disappearing. The result is significant unemployment in countries where labour prices are high compared to other economies.
Since private capital has no social responsibility and hence no responsibility for the unemployment it creates, the social charges of the State necessarily increase.
This whole situation intensifies the perfect unwillingness of the entrepreneurs to pay taxes and thus compensate for the economic and social damage caused to the whole of society by this race for profit.
This situation is so well known that it is not necessary to provide concrete statistical data.
The unscrupulous practices of private capital create in different economies a situation in which the governments of different countries are forced to engage in mutual competition in order to artificially lower the social level of their own population in order to attract foreign capital to them.
In other words, governments put their own people at the mercy of private capital without regard to social collapse.
This is manifested mainly in the amendments of the laws in force.
The objective is to economically force its own population to accept the diktat of private capital prices, especially in the field of wages.
This is due, on the one hand, to a system of economic constraints in the event of long-term unemployment and, on the other hand, to the restriction of the rights of employees in the field of labour legislation.
The result is growing poverty and deepening differences between the rich and the poor.
In the FRG, for years there have been public food distribution points for the poor who cannot provide for themselves with their own labour.
There are already millions of these people.
In the context of increasing the competitiveness of the German economy, it is becoming quite common for employees to receive such wages that the state is forced to pay a supplement so that they reach the subsistence minimum.
Such a scandal has been exposed, for example, in the case of employees working as auxiliaries in the federal parliament.
The economic measures of practically all the southern Member States of the EU undoubtedly generate a similar situation in which, under the pressure of a catastrophic collapse of society, people are forced either to emigrate (as was the case in the nineteenth century) or to live with poverty wages, on the margins of society, in the hope that one day private capital will be forced to emigrate.
The question here is: where will this capital come from?
If it comes from other EU countries, then poverty will pass from one country to another; this capital may not come either, or else a Chinese, an Indian, a Brazilian, a Turk, a Moroccan, an Egyptian or an African will continue to work for a fraction of a European salary.
This also applies to all of Latin America.
Liberal theory and the media claim, to tire of it, that the state cannot make capital investments in its own economy, that the directed economy leads to an economic catastrophe.
Private capital strongly defends the idea that the state cannot intervene in the economy through regulatory interventions.
It is then necessary to ask whether private capital does not influence and, even, does not today, according to its own selfish interests, direct politics and, by the same token, the entire State.
The answer to this question is undoubtedly yes.
The proof is that there is a virtually all-powerful lobby present in every state.
The result is a desperate situation manifesting itself in the field of corruption, through the granting of mutual advantages, in legislation, where everything is reprehensible but not punishable.
In the FRG, the situation is such that, due to the lack of financial resources, national ministries delegate the drafting of legislation to law firms closely linked to industry.
These bills are then passed in the Bundestag.
The totality of power does not come from the people, as Western-style constitutions declare, but from powerful financial groups serving their own interests.
It is clear that liberal-oriented democracies are now quickly confronted with the situation described by Appianos in his book entitled "The Crisis of the Roman Empire in the Times of Caesar and Pompey": "The state had long been in a state of decay and functions were attributed by violence.
Bribes, illegally obtained favors, and stones and swords were also used to obtain these positions.
The under-tables and corruption proliferated without limits and the people went to the elections with votes already sold"... "Honest people did not seek themselves in any way to obtain functions, it resulted once the state remained 8 months without consuls absolute".... ' It began to be said that the real remedy to this difficult situation was an autocracy, and that it was necessary to choose a 'c'
In conclusion, as in antiquity, present-day society is based on the preference for personal profit, without regard for the interests of society as a whole.
In its essence, private capital is no longer capable of understanding and asserting the interests of society as a whole.
The result, today as in the past, is an unprecedented decadence of elites, with no effort to carry out profound reforms.
We must therefore seek the causes of the emergence of fascist and communist regimes in the unscrupulous liberalization of the economic systems of the nineteenth and twentieth centuries.
As things stand, the disappearance of these systems in favour of liberal democracies can be seen as a kind of pause before a new stage.
The fact that today's elites are completely unaware of the possibility of hundreds of thousands of future loss of life, the humanitarian and social crises of which we are now witnessing, as well as the crimes against humanity as we know them from ancient and recent history.
Repeal of the Public Works Act is not a solution, at least in the long term.
Under the pressure of economic competition, both at the international level and at the European level, the Government of the Czech Republic will be forced to continue to look for ways to reduce the social level of the population.
This trend is indeed systemic.
The solution is socio-political reforms, which will strengthen state capital investment in the economy, increase citizens' influence over the government and weaken the monopoly position of private capital in society for the benefit of the state.
