People want me to save the Republic, but I'm just an amateur, says Senator Okamura
Senator, how do you propose to run in the presidential election?
It's not being a senator or president that matters to me.
If everything worked smoothly in our country, I would not be a candidate anywhere.
But I can no longer bear to see how the country has been looted for the past twenty years, that thieves are not under lock and key and the retirement age is rising.
I didn’t have the ambition to become a politician.
But when I see something I don't like, then I try to find a way to make it change.
And since I am over forty years old and I am independent, a member of no party, I have no other way to influence the situation than to run in presidential or senatorial elections.
You entered the Senate but you quickly set off for the Castle. (Editor’s note: Chair’s seat).
Do you not turn your backs on those who have elected you?
I've always said I'll go into battle for the Castle based on the results of the Senate election.
Later, I made it clear that if I were elected senator, I would run in the presidential election.
My goal is not the function, it is only an instrument allowing me to realize my vision.
That is why I need the greatest influence and the broadest mandate.
The problem is not only that as a nation we grumble at the bar or in front of our television set, but also that we stomp on all those who are trying to bring about change.
Added to this is the press that breaks the reputation of people and confuses freedom of speech with freedom to lie.
For example, it was said about me that I bribe journalists or that I was an adviser to Ji<0xC5><0x99><0xC3><0xAD> Paroubek.
Let’s come to your visions.
You started the fight for the Castle with the themes of the material and criminal liability of politicians and retroactive tax returns beyond twenty million [CZK] as a workhorse.
To that end, you need to change the law.
As president, you do not have that power, and only the Senate as a whole can propose legislation.
How do you want to solve this problem?
When, as a citizen, I lobbied for tour guide activities to be a liberal profession, I won.
The problem is politicking: when someone comes from the left or the right with a good project, it is knowingly refused and delays the citizens.
As an independent, not a member of any party, I have a much better chance of getting the support of all parliamentary parties.
I have the advantage of being able, without partisan categorization and dogma, to take from each party what is best for our country and implement it.
Do you see yourself as a right or a leftist?
From a Czech point of view, I have the impression that people place me rather on the left.
For me, whether it's a little left or right, it's not really important.
The important thing for me is that we move forward.
What matters to me is not that people are left-wing or right-wing, but that we bring people together.
I always support any solution that contributes to the common good, even if it is proposed by the Communist Party or ODS and I act equally impartially against bad ideas.
Do you get angry when someone says you are a populist?
But doesn't what you said prove it?
When you develop a business plan in a company, you also have a certain optimal goal and vision.
You're trying to get close to it.
Some may call it populism, but all the proposals I speak of have been applied by the world and recognized experts have spoken about it.
But without the support of parliament, all you have left are slogans.
You won’t survive long in politics with this.
Do you think that if you go to see people and talk to them, you will succeed, for example, in imposing material and criminal responsibility?
I don't have any other options.
I need to convince politicians, journalists and public opinion and try to rally them to my side in order to impose it.
If I were elected president, it would not be a problem to broadcast live on television my request to the presidents of parliamentary parties to legislate on the material and criminal responsibility of politicians, civil servants, judges and prosecutors.
They should then eventually explain why they don’t want it.
When there is a strong personality who will identify the abuses, it will be possible to put pressure on the political scene.
Take for example the election of the president by direct suffrage, it was obtained thanks to the pressure of public opinion.
I confess, without ambiguity, to be an amateur, and not a genius or an intellectual.
I try to find allies for my opinions and visions.
I just got into politics and I'm trying to get the support of the majority for my program.
I'm trying to get things done on my own, and if that doesn't work, I'll quit in six years and go back to the private sector.
It's almost as if Okamura is going to save the Czech Republic.
I'm not a saviour.
I know that one person cannot make a difference, which is why I went to see a number of personalities and asked them to stand in the Senate elections as well.
I met Radim Jan<0xC4><0x8D>ura, but he refused because of the amount of work.
I at least supported the investigative journalist Jana Lorencová who exposed the fuel frauds.
I introduced myself because people are really unhappy but now I hesitate.
Sixty percent of the people did not vote and what did, for the most part, gave their vote to a representative of the establishment.
In the Senate, we are just two independents.
The people have elected a Senate that can hardly impose change.
In spite of everything, I will fight for my vision, for example the election by direct suffrage of mayors and prefects of regions.
Are you planning to start your own party?
No, not yet, because I don't have time to check if every potential member's past is spotless and then I don't have the financial means.
I don’t have any money for my presidential campaign either, I only have twenty thousand in my “transparent” account.
Don't you have any money?
If you’re talking about tax returns, what’s yours?
I estimate the value of my personal property to be about $60 million.
I have in Prague a plot of land worth 25 million, an apartment worth 10 million, another apartment worth 8 million, a collection of works of art worth about 10 million, an Aston Martin worth 3.5 million and a <0xC5><0xA0>koda Superb worth 1 million and a few million on my account.
By the way, I own an Aston Martin, because it was a kid’s dream: I’ve always loved James Bond, who drove cars, was gallant with women and fought against evil and abuse.
You drive an Aston Martin, you have a fortune worth $60 million and you don't have any money for your campaign?
You want to change the Republic but you don’t want to invest your own money in it?
That's not very convincing.
I don't have $15 million for this campaign.
Should I go into debt?
I've already invested two and a half million in the campaign.
The fact that I do not have any sponsors shows that my program does not generate much interest.
I don't have to pay for this campaign out of my own pocket.
My campaign expenses are generally covered by the compensation I will receive as a senator.
But I couldn't afford it, like paying for my son's English school, which costs 30 grand a month.
If my only goal was to make money, I will not stand for election.
