The architects of the firm MVRDV prove that true adventures are not just a matter of imagination. To be convinced, just look at Spijkenisse and the newly erected mountain of books - 2 photos
"I think this building is funny, it's very futuristic, finally something interesting to see," says Lisette Verhaig, a passerby on the side of the street.
Stefan Spermon, a computer scientist at a large company nearby, tells us: "Yes, it is indeed beautiful, this building".
But I wonder why we still need a library today.
Everyone has the Internet, an iPad, and e-books.
Today, no one goes voluntarily to one of these nerdy libraries, right?
Spijkenisse, a dormitory town that has nothing attractive about the gates of Rotterdam, holds a rather special record.
The 80,000-strong municipality has the lowest education rate in the Netherlands.
In order to give some neurons back to the brains, the city decided, a few years ago, to contribute to the general culture and to reproduce the seven fictitious bridges that appear on the euro banknotes in the form of pretty small miniatures in painted reinforced concrete.
The success of the cultural offensive remained limited.
This is how the city authorities realized that there was only one way to regain control over the statistics: the construction of a library!
Winy Maas of the Rotterdam architectural firm MVRDV, master of bold stick diagrams and creator of witty and often cynical buildings, accepted the project with his usual phlegm and entered the competition in 2003 with five books under his arm and a snicker on his face.
And while the members of the jury were still looking at each other, bewildered and shrugging their shoulders, Maas, the cheeky one, stacked his choice books in order of size to make a pyramid, and ended his speech supported by activist arguments with one: "common dear!"
Here it is, my proposal for the mountain of books of Spijkenisse, or as they say, the Boekenberg!
Nine years later, the mountain of 30 million euros has sprung from the ground.
The building is part of a revitalization project that also includes underground parking, a supermarket, a post office and some buildings and terraced houses for a total of 50 homes.
At the beginning of November, the mountain of books received the second prize "Best Library of NL 2012".
In addition, the project was selected for the Dutch National Wood Award 2012.
Thus, this drab little town, which until today had nothing more to offer than a postmodern pedestrian area and a town hall of mind-boggling ugliness, whose white facades suggest that they are home to a dairy, has been enriched with a contemporary architectural work.
Most importantly, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in its history.
The Long Road to Reading
First impression: Eldorado of the book under a cheese bell.
Certainly, an elevator transports you to the heart of the massif, but the real joys of reading and architecture open up to you when you step on the ground of the building to discover its topography.
The interior made entirely of glass is bright and clear, the Dutch brick floor and elegant streetlights speak unequivocally the language of municipal public squares.
The urban atmosphere is perfect.
We are already looking for public benches, dogs and little boys and girls who play with the ball.
And everywhere books, books and more books.
“Normally, library shelves are located along the fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade and in the middle is a large, dark room, which is often uncomfortable and impersonal,” says Maas.
We have completely overturned the classical spatial configuration and opened the reading spaces from the inside out.
The interior of the mountain of books has been skillfully arranged: in the middle are the offices, the Internet library, the chess club, the center for the environment and the technical central building.
A particular beauty lies in the black shelves of the library, which are sometimes paneling, sometimes balustrades, sometimes staircase ramps.
A new experience for sight, touch and smell.
Even hardened architects and building engineers don’t want unknown materials.
“We wanted to work with recycled materials,” says Joop Trouborst, project manager at the municipality of Spijkenisse, in a response to the Standard.
This is how one day we found in a Frisian agricultural company an ad hoc waste from agriculture.
In the Netherlands, synthetic membrane one millimetre thick has been used for years as a substrate in greenhouses and fields.
It is cheap and saves time.
The thin membrane is used for one or two seasons, then it can be discarded.
For the library, the membrane was compressed, for the first time in such quantities, into plates with a thickness of four centimeters.
Under the effect of heat and pressure, the "Landbouwplastic" (KPL) changes color and turns into a dark, homogeneous and resistant material, the smell of which evokes both a new car and sports shoes.
At the top of the 105 steps is the top of the mountain.
At the end of almost 500 meters, the literary café offers us a breathtaking view of the city, but also Dutch croquettes and ficus in pots.
The latter create an atmosphere, but they contribute above all to the maintenance of the ideal level of humidity of the air of the literary mountain.
Gifts for the New Soul
“It’s incredible, but despite all the glass surfaces, this building is a model project in terms of ecology,” says Trouborst.
The temperature of the building is regulated by geothermal energy.
Although the mountain of books is located below a glass bell, the sun only illuminates the interior for a short time, even on sunny days.
The thick wooden beams mounted at right angles to the glass fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade serve as a sun visor, intercepting a large part of the rays.
The atmosphere is very pleasant.
Fully automated blinds take care of the rest.
Stefan Spermon, the aforementioned septic computer scientist, has already risked entering the new library.
Lisette Verhaig was already there.
Cynthia Bogarde, professor of traditional Chinese medicine, even describes the Boekenberg as "the soul finally found" of Spijkenisse.
A few weeks ago, during the inauguration, each citizen was invited to donate a book from his personal library.
This measure made it possible to fill the gaps in the library that was not yet completely filled (today it has 70,000 books).
The concept is a success.
The rays are overflowing on all sides.
Architect Winy Maas once said, “There is nothing worse than a half-empty library.”
"I believe our invitation has created a certain relationship between each citizen and this new building.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this edifice.
Even if it's just for decoration."
This is how MVRDV has achieved the master discipline that is called, in professional jargon, "the creation of an identity".
Spijkenisse has written a new page of literary history.
She may seem young and uneducated.
Finally, it is a new starting point for the birth of an identity.
Szabo: "The Germans must play a bigger role."
Germany abstained in the vote on the admission of the Palestinian state.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on US-EU relations, this decision puts Berlin in a delicate political situation.
Deutsche Welle: Earlier this week, Germany announced its intention to vote against the Palestinians’ request for observer status at the United Nations.
But then she chose to abstain.
Why is that?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not approve of what the Israelis did in Gaza.
However, Berlin needs to be cautious, as it has special relations with Israel.
But I also don't think it supports the American position.
Germany wanted to assert its independence, but was not overly critical of Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany had also chosen to abstain in the vote on the establishment of a no-fly zone.
In the end, NATO imposed this measure.
Is Germany having difficulty in taking a clear position on major international issues?
The answer is yes.
The reason for this is that Berlin is in the process of reviewing its foreign policy, seeking to move away from a policy as it were defined by the Americans and to establish a German foreign policy.
Moreover, the lack of a coherent and common policy within the Union complicates the situation.
The Germans faced several fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I believe they are still groping for this role, but are on the way to a "more normal" foreign policy.
A foreign policy, as in France or Great Britain
What, then, does the term “normal” foreign policy actually mean for the Germans?
It shows a willingness to adopt positions independent of those of the United States and European partners, including on national issues.
I believe that German foreign policy is also determined by its economic policy, therefore by exports and its relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany's economic interests are, to some extent, different from those of the other major powers: that is why Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced Germany's position on the conflict in the Middle East and its abstention in the United Nations vote?
Germany initially had important opportunities in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf countries.
