Brand protection in China: when Puma and Armani suddenly become Chinese
Armani and Polo Ralph Lauren are well-known brands around the world.
Armani Polo... what is it really about?
Behind this name hides a trademark officially registered in China, but which has nothing to do with the original company.
The trade mark thus enjoys such protection that the undertaking bearing its name cannot lodge a complaint.
And even if she could, he's not sure she'd win the case.
“It’s becoming increasingly difficult for foreigners to protect their trademarks in China,” said Thomas Pattloch, a lawyer with the law firm Taylor Wessing who specializes in property infringement in the Far East.
Every week, a new file arrives on my desk.
Imitators only need a few extra letters to be able to register their trademarks.
So instead of Gucci, we record Lu-Gucci, and instead of Prada, we record Prada-Kny.
German companies are also legally copied, such as Puma, the manufacturer of sporting goods.
Pattloch opens a filing cabinet containing the registrations made with the Beijing Trademark Office.
On September 14, 2010, a Chinese company filed the trademark Zegna DF Puma, a name that the firm artificially created by appropriating part of the name of Ermenegildo Zegna, the fashion house.
It is a known fact that the Chinese have become the world champions of copying and infringement of intellectual property.
In large cities, there are multi-storey shopping malls that sell practically only counterfeit goods.
Pattloch's cases, however, are different: his constituents instruct him to address the fact that the Chinese Trademark Office officially grants Chinese companies the right to use a name that is already protected in another country.
The Chinese speak of "Bang Mingpai", a related brand.
The term is derived from "Bang Dakuan".
It is with this term that women who marry rich men are referred to.
The Chinese authorities say they have nothing to complain about.
“It’s bad for business, you have to fight this trend,” Pattloch said.
“The brand is watered down, the uniqueness disappears, the damage to reputation is huge.”
Financial losses and court costs are in the millions for the sectors concerned, especially for expensive flagship products.
According to data from market analysis firm CLSA, China represents, with an annual volume of 15 billion euros, the world’s third-fastest-growing and fastest-growing luxury goods market.
However, it is not easy to remove dubious registrations from the trademark register and these procedures are expensive.
The latter can last up to nine years, and the outcome is never certain.
Pattloch recounts the trials in which the court dismissed the complaint, because after a long time, the criticized denomination had become a “market reality.”
Pattloch explains that if the complainant is unlucky, he may even be forced to pay money to the plagiarist because it would have harmed his brand in China.
In this area, it is sometimes the law of the jungle that dominates.
Famous cases also concern graphic elements.
In 2009, Daimler lost a legal battle against the construction machine manufacturer Sany, the same company that had just bought the concrete pump producer Putzmeister.
This is the reason why the Chinese can use an emblem that looks like the Mercedes star.
Geely, the buyer of Volvo, used a blue and white logo that resembled that of BMW. The conflict was settled and Geely had to change it.
The fashion house Lacoste had lost against plagiarists from Hong Kong and Singapore who had reoriented the look of the famous crocodile in the opposite direction.
According to the Chinese authorities, they are not guilty of anything.
The CTMO trademark office in Beijing admits, however, to having experienced some difficulties in 2010 due to a lack of staff and space.
However, the office would have gone last year from an "emergency situation in the course of the work to a normalcy regained".
Thus, the number of untreated opposition proceedings would have decreased by 22%.
Nearly 57,000 such cases would have been closed, representing a 75% increase over the previous year.
However, 81,500 cases are still pending at the Office.
Acting is expensive
As is often the case in China, the numbers are impressive.
Last year, the CTMO received more than 1.4 million trademark applications, almost a third more than in 2010.
According to the office, this is a record and means that China is at the top of the ranking for the tenth time in a row for the number of new deposits in the world.
This would also apply to the total number of legal marks, which is 5.5 million.
In 2011, the office reportedly accounted for 1.8 billion yuan of registration fees.
In other words, each record brought in an average of 1,280 yuan, or 160 euros.
A legal battle costs much more, as illustrated by the case of the German family business Freudenberg.
For more than seven years, the company has been fighting a Chinese plagiarist.
Admittedly, the Germans were able to get the illegal manufacture of vehicle components suspended.
However, the imitator was able to maintain its Chinese rights to the Freudenberg trademark.
“It’s our fault, because surnames cannot be protected in Germany,” explains Hanno Wentzler, CEO of Freudenberg Chemical Specialities in Munich.
The trade mark office had therefore rejected the Munichers' objection.
Freudenberg won the case in the following two instances, but the opposing party continues to fight to this day.
Vigilance is required
Today, the case is pending before the Supreme Court.
Wentzler is confident, he believes in a positive outcome of the trial and praises the professionalism of the judges.
Nevertheless, he adds: "the procedure is long, grueling and costs us a lot of time and money."
It is also difficult to assess internal costs, and the archives department has even had to review the actions of the last hundred years in order to provide evidence.
Five years ago, Freudenberg even proposed in vain to the opposing party a "large six-figure euro sum" to settle the dispute.
“That’s what it means to us,” Wentzler says.
The dangers of the Far East even threaten to spill over into Europe.
This would be the case if imitators of this region were to ensure the exploitation of unprotected marks.
For example, a Chinese producer wanted to file in Germany the name Freudenberg for a shoe and leather production company.
The company had long since abandoned this sector, but it had still been able to prevent the filing.
Wentzler adds: "vigilance is in order."
Pattloch and he advise German companies to exercise great caution in their trade relations with China.
It is not enough, according to them, to rely on international trademark law, foreigners should rather "also register in China everything that is likely to be protected", as Wentzler says.
Otherwise, the costs can be much higher than those of registration.
Indeed, if Freudenberg lost the battle in the last act of his legal drama, the company would have to pay licensing fees to the opposing party for the use of its own name, as Wentzler explains.
Otherwise, we would lose our place in the segment of the market in question.
