Fifty singers from 23 to 69 years old have come, from the geneticist in human medicine to the homemaker.
"Om'Obani" is not an easy song, each chorister has different lyrics, all in a very exotic language: Zulu, a language spoken by 11 million people in South Africa, Botswana, Lesotho, Malawi, Mozambique and parts of Swaziland.
Being Helped to Help Yourself
UNAIDS, the United Nations AIDS programme, estimates that 34 million people worldwide are affected by the disease.
23.5 million of them live in southern Africa.
Swaziland has 245,000 infected people.
In addition, more than 40% of the population is HIV-positive.
180 AIDS orphans from the village of Esitjeni found sponsors in Germany thanks to the association "Voices for Africa".
70 of them attend a secondary school.
For 15 or 20 euros less, you can become a sponsor.
This amount guarantees the child money for school, a school uniform and a daily hot meal at the gogo center.
Imbongi means in Zulu "storyteller" or "singer of praise".
No one can speak the Bantu language fluently in this region, but everyone can sing it.
For almost 10 years, the choir has been repeating songs in this foreign language that it brought to Germany to now return to its native region: the South of Africa.
For at 8,733 kilometers in a bird's eye view of Heidelberg, in the North-West of the Kingdom of Swaziland, is Esitjeni, the village that depends on the vocal power of the German choir.
40% of people affected
The village has about 2,000 inhabitants, some living in modest straw or earth huts and the majority of them are children.
More than 300 of them are orphans because HIV has taken their parents away.
In Esitjeni, we can observe on a smaller scale the evils that overwhelm Swaziland: the highest rate of HIV infection and the lowest life expectancy in the world according to UNICEF.
The population almost never accepts male circumcision, a measure that nevertheless guarantees a proven reduction in the risk of infection by half.
More than 40% of Swaziland's population carries the immunodeficiency virus and it is not uncommon to die in your mid-thirties.
During a group trip to Africa in the spring of 2005, the choir had been able to discover the village. The Imbongis especially saw many children in the street who lacked not only parental care, but also simply everything: food, clothing, education.
In a poor country without a school diploma, there is simply no prospect.
In the beginning, it was just a few people who personally committed to pay a few euros each year so that they could send a child to school and offer him a hot meal a day.
But just a year later, the choir founded "Voices for Africa", an association that since then has dealt almost professionally with AIDS orphans in Esitjeni.
Facts about Sexually Transmitted Infections
What are the most common sexually transmitted diseases?
Bacterial STIs include syphilis, chlamydia, and gonorrhea.
Common STIs are HIV, human papillomavirus, genital herpes, or hepatitis.
Pubic lice and scabies belong to parasitic STIs.
What are the main groups concerned?
Syphilis and gonorrhoea often appear in men who have sex with other men.
The Robert Koch Institute estimates that sexual contact between men is the cause of at least four out of every five cases of syphilis reported in Germany.
In heterosexual adults, chlamydial-related infections, trichomoniasis, candidiasis (fungal), gonorrhea, and human papillomavirus are common sexually transmitted diseases.
The rate of spread of HIV among heterosexual adults is relatively low in Germany; however, some 20% of new HIV infections occur in this group.
A significantly higher rate of chlamydial-related infections is observed in young people than in other population groups.
According to European surveys, three-quarters of all infections are among young people aged 15 to 25.
In addition, in Germany, the human papilloma virus is common in young people.
What is the evolution of the number of infections?
It is not mandatory to report all sexually transmitted diseases.
According to the Robert Koch Institute, the number of syphilis cases has more than doubled in 10 years, from 1,967 in 2001 to 3,698 in 2011.
Since 2007, the number of new HIV infections has been declining.
In 2011, there were about 2,700 cases.
This represents a decrease of one tenth compared to the previous year.
What are the symptoms of a sexual illness?
Infectious diseases can cause abscesses in the genitals, urinary pain, white discharge, pain in the lower abdomen as well as the appearance of pimples and warts.
However, they do not regularly cause any pain or other symptoms and therefore remain hidden.
How to protect yourself?
Condoms can reduce the risk of infection, but they do not protect 100%.
The reason for this is that pathogens of sexually transmitted diseases can also be transmitted through lubricating infection or through close body contact.
Experts therefore recommend that anyone who often changes sexual partners should have regular check-ups.
Most rapidly detected STIs can be cured and late sequelae can be avoided.
