He was in power until 2003, when his son Ilham succeeded him.
In any case, elderly people in Azerbaijan do not experience distress.
Mirzayeva receives monthly 230 manats (about the same amount as in euros) for her retirement, a sum that guarantees a good lifestyle in the region.
And perhaps Mirzayeva’s long-greyed son is right: “the elders enjoy great respect in our culture.”
They are the center of the big family, they are loved, cared for and happy.
This is a good reason to live as long as possible.
The "Rights of Man" Omitted in the Constitution
The revolution is reborn in Cairo.
Rival demonstrations reveal the deep fracture of the country.
The draft Sharia-based constitution is fiercely controversial.
The Egyptian president is not stingy with words full of emotions.
We must succeed in the transition.
“And this success is my responsibility to the people and to God,” he said on state television.
His speech was intended for the entire people, but also especially for Christian Copts, liberals, enlightened Muslims and lay people.
Because all members of the confused and hopelessly disunited opposition are afraid.
They are afraid of a theocracy on the Nile in the hands of the powerful Muslim Brotherhood.
Mohamed Morsi said, almost apologizing, that he had temporarily restricted the powers of the Constitutional Court and expanded its powers “in order to save the revolution.”
However, Egyptians and the world do not really know what this 61-year-old engineer, who holds a doctorate from the American University of Southern California, wants to save.
Will the judiciary be overthrown?
The 234 hastily drafted articles by the predominantly Islamic 100-strong Constituent Assembly during a 15-hour nightly tour of force are indeed worrisome to some extent.
As in previous constitutions, the draft provides for case law to be based on "the principles of Islamic law".
What does the word “principles” really mean?
This was and still is a question of interpretation, and there is good reason to fear that Islamists will use the vague wording and the resulting legal leeway to enforce a stricter interpretation of Sharia law.
In any case, this suggests a newly introduced article stating that, with regard to all subjects related to Sharia, al-Azhar University should be consulted. The establishment is the most important Islamic institution in the country and its brilliance radiates throughout the Sunni Islamic world.
This may, but does not necessarily mean that the clergy will supervise the legislative apparatus, which would result in the de facto placing of the judicial power under guardianship.
Many points of the draft Constitution are subject to interpretation.
Another problematic aspect is the likely maintenance of military jurisdiction.
During Mubarak's reign, these courts worked to suppress opponents.
After the fall of the dictator, up to 11,000 civilians were detained by the military.
The government must also protect “the true nature of the Egyptian family” and “promote its morals and values.”
From a legal point of view, the formulation is so vague that state institutions could even control the content of cinematographic art and literature.
In other words, it would simply be censorship.
Moreover, there is no explicit guarantee of equality between men and women in any of the articles.
Instead, another article forbids offending or defaming the Prophet Muhammad or his envoys.
However, the article does not define what an offence is or how it should be punished.
Equally dubious is the wording suggesting that it is forbidden to "offend people".
Is it enough to draw a caricature of the president or tell a joke at the expense of a lawman?
Many points are therefore subject to interpretation in the draft that Morsi submits to the vote and which, in his own words, will "very soon" be the subject of a referendum with the Egyptians.
"The revolution is reborn"
The opposition has been mobilizing for weeks against the numerical superiority of the Islamists.
On Friday evening, tens of thousands of demonstrators rallied in an unusual concord in Cairo’s Tahrir Square, vowing to bring down Sharia law before it takes effect.
"The revolution is reborn and we will win," said Hamdin Sabbahi, who came third in the presidential election.
Nobel Peace Prize winner and former head of the International Atomic Energy Agency Mohamed El Baradei said the draft constitution is “to be thrown into the dustbin of history”.
On Twitter, the instant messaging service, he accused Morsi supporters of wanting to foment a “putsch against democracy.”
"If he proclaims the referendum, we will go to his palace and overthrow him," said Jasser Said, an opponent.
“We are not tired yet, the blood of our brothers is not yet expiated,” said Khaled Ali, a politician and member of the opposition, according to Egyptian media.
In addition, several judges announced that they did not want to monitor the referendum, which would result in its nullity.
"The Qur'an is our Constitution"
For its part, the Muslim Brotherhood, well organized, called for a counter-demonstration not in Tahrir Square as a precautionary measure, but on the other bank of the Nile, where a large prayer was organized in front of Cairo University.
The veiled women and supporters of the Salafists, who participated in large numbers, chanted: "The people demand the application of the law of God."
“Cleanse our country!” they asked Morsi, claiming that “the Koran [was their] Constitution.”
A struggle for sovereignty over the symbolic Tharir Square, where it all began, would soon have generated a situation similar to that of a civil war.
Clearly, this is what Morsi’s supporters wanted to avoid.
The Muslim Brotherhood said opponents of the draft constitution, along with its supporters, had spoken out loudly.
According to them, it is now time to let the people decide by the ballot box which direction the country should take.
The Islamists’ project will certainly win the majority.
"Human rights are not mentioned only once"
Hafez Abu Saeda is angry at this imposed constitutional process which should have lasted until February and encompassed all social forces.
The 48-year-old human rights lawyer and president of the Egyptian Organization for Human Rights (EOHR) had defended the Muslim Brotherhood when they were in prison or in court under Mubarak.
He did so not because he shared their worldview, but because for him human rights are indivisible.
This is why he was beaten, tried and imprisoned.
"And now the term is not even pronounced once in the new constitution," he said in an interview with the Welt am Sonntag newspaper.
The extension of Morsi’s powers to the three powers discouraged the lawyer.
These measures are blatant violations of the rules of democracy and will lead to a new dictatorship in Egypt.
“Instead of strengthening civil society, the president is de facto stripping it of all its powers,” Saeda said.
Yet a democracy cannot function without civil society organizations.
Saeda feels neglected, including by the international community, which looks at the battle between different political ideologies on the banks of the Nile with a mixture of curiosity and nervousness.
It could pay off.
A protester in Tharir Square warns: "you are giving birth to a monster that you will no longer be able to control."
Norway’s rakfisk: is it the most fragrant fish in the world?
The five million people who live in Norway enjoy one of the highest standards of living, not only in Europe, but also in the world.
Could the secret to the country’s success be linked to the locals’ appetite for an extremely fragrant fish?
Take advanced cheeses.
Place them in the middle of a pile of wet and dirty soccer clothes.
Wait a week.
And you get the disturbing smell of rakfisk, one of Norway's most popular dishes.
I am in the small town of Fagernes, about 3 hours from Oslo.
It snows, the scenery is spectacular - and this smell, omnipresent, permeates the air.
The rakfisk consists of trout sprinkled with salt and fermented in water for a duration - depending on the smell you want it to exhale - which can go up to a year.
When darkness sets in and it gets cold, Norwegians gather en masse to attend a festival here in Fagernes dedicated to this incredible culinary speciality.
“You eat raw, then you swallow a glass of aquavit,” says Havard Halvarsen, a full-time local firefighter who is also known as “Rakfisk General,” who is in charge of managing the festival.
Around us, people swallow small pieces of fish and put on a large amount of drink.
“Some people prefer aquavit to rakfisk,” adds Havard.
The drink kills the smell.
I'm trying out a few pieces.
If you can avoid putting it under your nose, it’s not bad – it’s reminiscent of a sushi that would have spent long hours on a bus.
The rakfisk dates back to a time when Norway was poor, before the invention of refrigeration, the fish was immersed in airtight water barrels, then salted in autumn.
Then, during the winter, once well fermented, the fish came out and - undoubtedly with the senses impaired by alcohol - ate.
In the previous generation, thousands of Norwegians were forced to leave their country to find work, emigrating mainly to the United States.
Now, the population is growing rapidly - more than 13% are immigrants, attracted by full employment, high wages and a comprehensive health system.
The Swedes, their old rivals whose country was not so long ago richer than Norway, cross the border to come to work.
The rakfisk is considered something important, a vital, though odorous, element of Norway's past.
This is one of the most expensive dishes.
But everything is expensive - a small pint of beer or a sandwich will cost you 10 € each.
Norway does not often make headlines in international news, which is not to its displeasure.
Here, people are not willing to talk about Anders Breivik, the right-wing extremist racist who shot dead 77 people, including women and children.
When they talk about this killing, they talk about the "July 22 incident".
The Norwegians find it difficult to accept that in their peaceful country, one of their own might have committed such an act of barbarism.
Since the early 1970s, Norway owes its wealth to its oil and gas industry, one of the largest in the world.
“But oil is not the only reason that justifies our success,” explains Anna, our waitress, with blonde hair and piercing blue eyes, the image of Nordic well-being, with a tray of rakfisk in her hand.
We are – as you say – cautious people.
Her English, like most of the people who live here, is perfect.
We are discreet, we do not like to be noticed.
Norway has managed its oil wealth very cautiously - everything, except a small percentage of money from this industry, is invested in a special fund for the benefit of future generations.
When other countries were throwing money out the window in the years leading up to the international financial crisis, Norway was able to keep its purse strings tight.
“As long as you can ski in the winter and hike in the summer, we’re happy,” says Anna.
“Not to mention the rakfisk,” she adds in a carefree laugh.
I stand in the snow and stand in line to buy something to eat - I got my dose of rakfisk.
On the menu, a burger made of moose, a real discovery, it is excellent.
But tonight, the smell of fish is everywhere.
The hotel I am staying in is one of the many places where rakfisk is served for dinner and where you can vote for the best of them - or perhaps the most fragrant of them.
There is a TV show where the presenter wears a bow tie, surrounded by rakfisk plates.
It looks like the Eurovision Song Contest.
"What score did you give the best fish in the Thor-Juergen Mountains?"
"Here's our points, Havard."
We hear laughter and applause.
A man falls out of his chair, perhaps because of the abuse of aquavit.
Or maybe it's because of the fish fumes.
Mexican Enrique Pena Nieto has a tough start.
As incoming President Enrique Pena Nieto prepares to take office in Mexico, Will Grant, of the BBC, takes an interest in the difficulties that await him and the expectations of the people, which are numerous.
Traffic in Mexico City is particularly bad at the moment.
In a city where traffic jams are common, a security barrier has been in place since Monday, blocking several key road accesses to the capital and causing real chaos on the roads.
Nevertheless, the aim was not to prevent people from going to their work, but to prevent protesters from reaching Parliament.
Next Saturday, Mexico’s new president, Enrique Pena Nieto, will receive the presidential sash to become the nation’s new president.
A complicated task awaits him.
Mexico's economy is doing well, a result that is owed to outgoing President Felipe Calderon, but the country is in the throes of a drug war that has already claimed the lives of about 60,000 people in six years.
“My government has made a commitment to the Mexican people to reduce violence,” Pena Nieto told U.S. President Barack Obama in the Oval Office earlier this week.
I will propose a new security strategy that will enable us to achieve this goal.
Before he met the US president, Pena Nieto was governor of Mexico.
A very populous and sprawling state that surrounds the capital. On his preferred land, opinions about this new leader are divided.
A direct man
In the bucolic town of Valle del Bravo, for example, it is inscribed in the memory of all.
The locals attribute it to the development of tourism and infrastructure in the municipality.
To reach the city, you can take one of the new highways of M Pena Nieto, a significant improvement has been made to these roads, once bumpy and full of crevasses.
Plaques bearing his name are hung outside a new sports complex and an impressive interactive museum dedicated to climate change.
“We are counting on him to bring about lasting change,” said his friend and political ally Gabriel Olvera Hernandez, a congressman and member of Pena Nieto’s party, the PRI.
In terms of security and economy, in particular, we hope for a real change that our country needs so much.
After 81 years in power, the PRI was ousted in 2000 by Vicente Fox.
Congressman Olvera admits that after 12 years spent outside the presidential palace in Los Pinos, there are high expectations within the party regarding Enrique Pena Nieto.
He rejects criticism from opponents who accuse the new president of lacking charisma.
He's a whole man, very committed, with an excellent vision of the country.
He is an excellent statesman and, above all, he knows how to listen.
However, this is not always the image that people have of their former governor.
In Nezahualcoyotl, also known as Ciudad Neza, the contrast with the cobbled streets of Valle del Bravo could not be more glaring.
Hidden under motorway bridges, it is, in many ways, a suburb of Mexico City.
And the problems in the municipality are also concrete and urban.
Earlier this year, members of the military were called to the rescue to fight drug gangs in neighbourhoods, where violence against women is particularly serious.
In a disaster area, the bodies of dozens of women murdered in the last two years were found on the edge of the landfill.
More than 1,000 women were killed in the state of Mexico while Mr. Pena Nieto was governor, a far higher rate than in the very violent city of Ciudad Juarez — a place infamous for the number of innocent women killed there.
Mr Pena Nieto's critics say that at best he has failed to curb the problem of murders committed against women when he was in office.
At worst, they accuse his administration of refusing to face reality.
In a concrete house, typical of this dilapidated neighborhood, Irinea Buendia struggles to hold back her tears when she shows me photos of her deceased daughter, Mariana Luna.
The official version mentions a suicide committed by Mariana in 2010.
However, her family believes she was killed by her partner.
“When I arrived at her house, it seemed to me that her body had been washed,” says Se<0xC3><0xB1>ora Buendia.
Signs indicated that she had been beaten, and cadaveric rigidity had already begun.
While her mother tells the story, a photo of Mariana dresses the wall, next to a cross where the word: Justice.
However, this is exactly what the family was denied.
The authorities treated me like I was an old gossip, a troublemaker, a whiner.
They want us to accept what they say and shut up.
“But it’s not normal that there are so many irregularities and omissions,” she said.
When President Pena Nieto receives her scarf on Saturday, she will carry a heavy responsibility.
Tens of thousands of families have been affected by crime in Mexico over the past six years, and the new president has vowed to make it his priority during his tenure.
“I hope he will be as good as he was as a governor,” Olvera told Valle del Bravo, a member of Congress.
However, this is exactly what the families of the victims of Ciudad Neza fear the most.
Bradley Manning has not complained of ill-treatment, prosecutors say.
Prosecutors are trying to counter claims of ill-treatment that Bradley Manning was allegedly subjected to while in detention.
The trial concerns Manning’s detention in a military prison in Quantico, Virginia.
The defense wants to close the case on the grounds that Manning's abduction took place under extremely difficult conditions.
The soldier is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents.
Prosecutors tried to show on Friday that Private Bradley Manning -- accused of causing the largest leak of confidential information in the history of the U.S. military -- has missed many opportunities to complain about the ill-treatment he claims to have suffered during his military detention.
In a cross-examination with Manning, during a preliminary hearing in Ft. Meade, Maryland, Attorney Maj. Ashden Fein claimed that recordings of weekly visits to Manning by officers during his nine-month detention in Quantico, Virginia, revealed no complaints about his treatment.
The cross-examination -- during a hearing, the defence filed a motion demanding that the Manning case be dismissed on the grounds that the seizure was carried out under very difficult conditions and constituted a sufficiently severe punishment -- took place one day after Manning testified that he wanted to commit suicide while in detention.
This military intelligence analyst, arrested in June 2010, is accused of having stolen thousands of confidential documents during his service in Iraq.
The documents were later published online by WikiLeaks.
WikiLeaks has never confirmed that Manning was their source.
At Friday’s hearing, Fein and Manning reviewed the forms officers had filled out after meeting Manning during his detention in Quantico Military Prison, where he was subjected to maximum solitary confinement from July 2010 to April 2011.
Officers asked Manning questions and recorded his answers.
When Fein mentioned the forms on Friday, Manning acknowledged that the treatment he received from his guards was "excellent" and that the treatment he had received in prison was overall "very professional."
The forms do not report any complaints of ill-treatment, although officers directly questioned him about his prison treatment, Fein said.
Manning replied that he had expressed concerns about certain issues orally and that the visiting officers had discussed his concerns and indicated that they would deal with them, but they did not record the issues raised.
"They wrote 'no problems' (after addressing the concerns), and yet that didn't mean I didn't raise any problems," Manning said.
Military Judge Col. Denise Lind also asked Manning why he did not complain about his treatment during an interview in January 2011 with the special commission that had met to discuss the suicidal thoughts he had expressed in writing a few months earlier.
Manning responded that his intention during the meeting was to have his restrictive status changed indicating a “risk of injury.”
The military said it assigned him this restrictive status -- one level below close surveillance for suicide risk -- for his protection and the safety of others.
“I wanted the staff to know that I was doing well, and I wanted to be removed from that status ... in order to benefit from a better quality of life from my point of view,” Manning said.
Manning testified Thursday about his arrest in Iraq and transfer to Kuwait, where he was held for nearly two months before being transferred to the military prison at the Marine Corps base in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He said he considered suicide when he was in Kuwait and fainted once because of the heat.
He added that not being kept informed of what was going to happen to him or what was happening in the rest of the world was very distressing.
“My world was reduced to Camp Arafjon, to this cage,” Manning said Thursday.
I thought I was going to die in that cage.
Once in Quantico, Manning said he spent most of his time in a small cell — at least 9 p.m. and sometimes more than 11 p.m. — without company.
Manning also added that the only items he had were a mattress, blanket, flip-flops, clothes and his glasses.
He tried to stay on the move because sleeping or lying down during the day was against the rules.
Manning also said that when he was trying to sleep, he had a light in his eyes, which was turned on outside his cell.
If the guards did not see his face when he turned at night, they would wake him up so they could see his face.
Manning’s lawyer filed a formal complaint for Manning’s treatment in January 2011.
Manning was placed in a military prison in Fort Leavenworth, Kansas, in April 2011.
Also Friday, the judge asked Manning questions about an allegation reported in his testimony Thursday -- that after being forced to sleep naked all night in his cell in Quantico, he was forced to stand naked in front of guards and other inmates one morning during the appeal.
Manning testified that at no time was she allowed to cover herself with a blanket during the call.
During the judge’s questions Friday, Manning said he inferred from his guard’s order that he had to let go of his cover that might have hidden his nudity, but he acknowledged that no one had ordered him to let go.
Manning testified Thursday that he was forced to sleep naked the night before because he allegedly tried to prove to an officer that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning reportedly told the officer that he could have used the elastic in his briefs or flip-flops to injure himself, but that he did not.
That night, Manning testified that his underwear, flip-flops, and glasses had been removed from his cell.
His lawyers hope that at least the judge will take into account the experiences he has experienced during his detention and that he will significantly reduce his sentence if he were to be convicted in a court martial, a trial that is expected to take place early next year.
The defense said Manning plans to plead guilty to the least serious offenses and fight for the dropping of other charges deemed too extreme.
The hearing is expected to resume this weekend, with prosecutors expected to argue that the conditions of detention were justified.
The Pentagon has confirmed that Manning was incarcerated in accordance with regulations governing the conditions of detention of all detainees at Quantico.
Charges against Manning include theft of public property or documents, collusion with the enemy, the illegal publication of information on the Internet, and the transmission of information relating to national defense.
If all the charges are upheld, he faces life imprisonment.
The Mexican-American Identity Crisis
He says many have been forced to leave Mexico because of the lack of opportunities
Mexicans tend to blame those who left; they remind Mexicans of difficult times, he said.
Navarrette says Mexican-Americans find themselves caught between two worlds.
On a recent trip to Mexico City, arriving in the lobby, in front of customs and immigration services, I felt lost.
Signs indicated two routes: one for the "Mexicanos" ("Mexicans"), another for the "Extranjeros" ("Foreigners").
I stood motionless for several seconds, not knowing which line to turn to.
I grew up in central California, where I’ve been called the “Mexican” all my life.
It’s an ethnic qualifier, just like the one my friends in Boston use when they call themselves “Irish,” or my friends in New York when they call themselves “Italian.”
Then I became a Mexican-American.
But, here, it was Mexico.
And in the land where my grandfather was born, there is no need for a special qualifier or a hyphen.
I was just an American.
I speak Spanish well enough to handle an interview in either language.
But I don't have the vocabulary of an Aboriginal, and I can't lose my American accent.
So I took my American passport and headed for the "Foreigners" line.
I thought back to that time of the week when Mexico’s new president, Enrique Pena Nieto, visited President Obama at the White House.
Generally, when the leaders of these two countries meet, their favorite themes are immigration, drugs, and trade.
Pena Nieto also wanted to talk about the growth of the Mexican economy, which is one of the reasons why Mexicans stay in Mexico rather than risk themselves in the United States.
He wants to ally with the United States and Canada, and create a Union for Trade on the model of the European Union, but in North America.
And Pena Nieto pledges to continue the war on drug cartels in Mexico, although he did not provide more details.
For Mexico, the relationship with the United States is complicated and bitter.
Most Americans have probably never thought about the fact that in 1848, the United States invaded Mexico and forced its leaders to cede half of their territory in writing at gunpoint.
But for Mexicans, who think in terms of centuries, and no minutes, memories are everywhere.
Therefore, as soon as a U.S. official makes the slightest criticism of Mexico, you begin to hear -- in the Mexican press, and among the elites -- complaints about how the Americans are undermining the sovereignty of their neighbor.
And Montezuma's kids are looking for a fight.
And yet, for Mexico, the most difficult relationship is the one that the country has with the more than 35 million Mexican-Americans who live in the United States.
Do you want to talk about bitterness?
There's a lot of them.
Mexico has its winners and losers, people for whom the country offers opportunities and others for whom the country does not.
The only reason that explains the large number of Mexican ancestors in cities like Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver or San Antonio, is that at some point, in our family tree, a person, perhaps a relative or a grandparent, did not find any opportunity in Mexico and had to go to the North.
And more often than not, that person matched a typical profile -- dark skin, poorly educated, from a poor village, etc.
We are their descendants, and we are loyal to them.
Not Mexico.
And even if we are currently living the American dream, that we have gone to good schools and that we have good situations, we must never lose sight of the fact that it is the American dream that we are living, and not that of the Mexicans.
Our identity is sometimes troubled, but our loyalty is obvious.
We grant it to the United States.
On the other hand, we know that part of the Mexican elite among the ruling class does not like us.
The feeling is mutual.
We remind them of a humiliating defeat and they tell us as if we were individuals of inferior stock and not Mexican enough.
Our Spanish will never be good enough, our ties with Mexico will never be strong enough.
For them, our existence is synonymous with failure.
If our families had not failed when they lived in Mexico, they would never have left.
And we would not find ourselves stuck on the right side of the fence, living comfortably in the United States, but as lost souls.
My wife, who was born in Guadalajara and legally immigrated to the United States as a child, reminds me that there is friction between Mexicans and Mexican-Americans, as Mexicans more firmly claim their identity and Mexican-Americans are annoyed by it.
Although she is an American citizen, she feels like she is part of two countries.
On the other hand, many Mexican-Americans I know do not feel like they are part of one country or the other.
We love the music of the Mexican band, Los Tigres del Norte, but also that of Bruce Springsteen.
We have the best of both worlds, but we are not rooted in either.
In Mexico, we are considered Americans.
And in the United States, we are considered Mexicans.
And now, to complicate the relationship a little more, as I learned during my stay, some Mexican leaders and a part of the intelligentsia want to get closer to the Diaspora.
They want Mexican-Americans to work as ambassadors of fortune for Mexico, representing its interests in the United States.
We will have to explain to our American compatriots that Mexico is a beautiful country that must be visited and put pressure on political leaders to strengthen ties with Mexico.
Yes, of course.
That's not gonna happen.
There's too much bitterness.
And when you consider the pervasive wage inequality, corruption and drug-related violence, many of us are not convinced that this is a fantastic country.
You're gonna have to fend for yourself, amigos.
It's normal.
If some Mexicans are not yet ready to forgive the United States for the way they treated Mexico a century and a half ago, they must therefore accept that some Mexican-Americans still resent them for the way their family members were treated not so long ago.
Mm-hmm.
Maybe we're more "Mexican" than I thought.
Old quarrels, new Middle East
The cease-fire between Israel and Hamas is still a failure for peace.
Will there ever be a lasting peace between Arabs and Jews in the Middle East?
Another bloodshed seems to indicate that such a hope is futile.
While the same futile arguments persist as to who started it, dozens of buildings have been reduced to dust; more than 140 Palestinians, most of them civilians, and six Israelis have been killed; and, for the first time, rockets fired from Gaza have landed near Tel Aviv, Israel’s metropolis, and the holy city of Jerusalem.
But although the Israelis and Palestinians seem stuck in their old conflict, all around them, the Middle East is in flux.
The Arab Spring has shattered everything, and whether we like it or not, the Palestinians and Israelis are caught up in this regional upheaval.
Perhaps their struggle will intensify even more.
Yet there is every reason to think it could help them get out of this deadly impasse.
A war that makes no losers and no winners
At first glance, it seems difficult to be optimistic.
Even as the Nov. 21 ceasefire holds, this week’s fighting has bolstered supporters of the force on both sides.
The leaders of Hamas, the Islamist movement that has ruled Gaza since 2007, will boast that they forced the Israelis to give up, even though Gaza was badly beaten.
Having killed some of its leaders and driven the 1.7 million inhabitants of Gaza into one of the most miserable and overcrowded corners of the planet, Israel has failed to destroy Hamas.
Indeed, Hamas is gaining ground in the West Bank, the other part of Palestine currently in the hands of their rivals Fatah, the other more moderate Palestinian faction.
Moreover, Hamas leaders might think that time is their ally.
The influence of Islamists in the Arab world is growing, and Hamas has made rich and powerful friends.
Turkey, a burgeoning regional power, once Israel’s closest Muslim ally, has made a case for Hamas; as has Qatar, one of the Gulf’s wealthiest and most dynamic states.
Hamas members are jubilant and say the Islamist crescent is curving around Israel, from Lebanon in the north, where Hezbollah’s militia exercises dominance, through Syria, where Islamist-leaning rebels can topple Bashar Assad, to Jordan, where Hamas allies threaten the king.
And most importantly, on Israel’s southern flank, the rise of the Muslim Brotherhood under the presidency of Muhammad Morsi in Egypt, by far the most populous and central of Arab countries, has changed the balance of the region.
Hosni Mubarak, the despot who ruled Egypt for 30 years until his fall in 2011, had little time to devote to Hamas.
The Muslim Brotherhood, on the other hand, are cousins of Hamas, and its leaders are more easily swayed by public opinion.
In future diplomacy, Hamas can emerge as an important actor that can no longer be excluded even by Israel and America.
Meanwhile, Israel’s hardliners will draw the opposite conclusions.
In military terms, Hamas has been boxed in.
The Iron Dome missile interception system has proven its effectiveness and many Hamas missiles have been destroyed.
The Israelis will be able to sleep on both their ears - for a while.
In terms of diplomacy, America is renewing its unwavering support; and many European countries have blamed Hamas for being behind the latest wave of violence.
But above all, Israel prospered, especially under Binyamin Netanyahu, the prime minister, who totally ignored the peace process.
Although rocket fire from Gaza has killed about 30 Israelis since 2004, Israel has been spared suicide bombings, thanks in part to the separation barrier that encroaches on the West Bank, the main piece of what could be a Palestinian state, and which protects Jewish settlements that continue to expand despite their illegality under international law.
Netanyahu, whose Likud party has merged with an even more hawkish party, that of leader Avigdor Lieberman in the run-up to the Jan. 22 election, has the bright side.
Why pamper these fucking Palestinians by giving them a state?
If they ruled the West Bank, would they not launch rockets, as their compatriots did in Gaza?
It’s best to keep them behind that wall and hit them as soon as they get their head out.
Perhaps the hardliners will win; but the Arab Spring may be a game-changer.
Even if the Islamists who take power in Egypt and elsewhere dislike Israel, their priority will be to tackle the problems in their own countries.
Israel’s defense budget is larger than that of its four Arab neighbors combined.
Starting a war with the local superpower will not help the new Arab governments to arrange their economies.
Morsi worked with Barack Obama to secure a ceasefire, which bodes well -- and could mark the beginning of something.
Israelis should also think about the future.
With the rest of the Arab world becoming more democratic, depriving Palestinians of their right to self-determination could create a powder keg that is destined to explode one day in Israeli-occupied territories – much like the bus that exploded in Tel Aviv this week.
Repression is already weakening democracy in the Jewish state, and demographics are exacerbating this problem as the Arab population increases.
