This is the case of Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 miners who make their living carrying the sulfur of the Kawah Ijen volcano, east of the Indonesian island of Java.
He must work every day to the bottom of the crater, where the sulfuric gas emanating from the bowels of the earth solidifies in contact with the air.
After collecting large sulfur rocks, which weigh a total of nearly 70 kilos, he installs them in two bamboo baskets that he loads on his shoulders through the steep paths.
There are only 250 meters to the summit of the volcano that culminates at 2,386 meters of altitude, but exhausted carriers take more than 40 minutes to climb this distance, at a turtle's pace, keeping the balance and measuring their steps so as not to stumble and fall into the precipice.
They know that a misstep could cost them their lives, as happened to a French tourist who made a fatal fall in the Kawah Ijen volcano several years ago.
Kawah Ijen miners earn 5 euro cents for every kilogram of sulphur extracted.
Once at the top, they make their way between the tourists who photograph them as if they were circus animals, and painfully carrying the heavy baskets, they walk the 3 kilometers to the scale that a mining company has installed a little below at 1,850 meters of altitude.
This is PT Candi Ngrimbi, a company that has been operating the volcano since 1960 and, we can say, its employees, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 euro cents) per kilogram of sulfur.
It then sells it for 10,000 rupees (83 euro cents) to the petrochemical industry since this ore is very present in daily life and is used to make candles, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even serves to bleach sugar.
“As we carry about 70 kilos, we earn about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) each trip,” explains Anto, who generally makes three trips per day.
Each one takes him 3 hours and he ends up exhausted, but this allows him to earn 138,000 rupees (11.50 euros) at the end of the day.
Although it seems to be a misery for such a superhuman effort, it is triple what it would gain in the fields.
“The income of the miners is very high here, where the coffee harvest is paid 15,000 rupees (1.20 euros) a day and where the average monthly salary is two million rupees (167 euros),” says the porter who once worked as a bricklayer on the tourist island of Bali.
There, his salary was 75,000 rupees (6.20 euros) per day and the job was not as difficult, but Anto returned close to his family in Banyuwangi, a village near the volcano, for a reason that, in Indonesia, is as indisputable as sulfur: "I married a girl from Bali, where they are Hinduists, and I converted her to Java".
Anto suffers from asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs constantly and his eyes are irritated by toxic gases.
At 27, he spent three of his life defying danger on the Kawah ljen, but sulfur has already begun to make him pay the bill even though he covers his face with a mask and wears special gloves.
Anto suffers from asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs constantly and his eyes are irritated by the toxic gases released by the volcano.
This is the price he must pay to pursue his dream.
“I’m going to work for two more years because I want to open a shop or study Spanish or French,” he promises in more than acceptable English.
Struck by life, this friendly and intelligent young man could be a tour guide, waiter or receptionist in a hotel, but instead he does the work of a mule.
It shares an unsanitary wooden house with other porters, rises every day at two in the morning because the sulfur does not stop gushing at night, when its characteristic yellow color becomes blue and shines in the middle of the darkness.
Defying the darkness, Anto descends into the crater while illuminating himself with a small lamp attached to his helmet, which he bought himself with his own money.
Some 400 porters load the sulfur baskets on their shoulders from the bottom of the crater.
Despite its comfortable benefits, the mining company has not mechanized the extraction of sulfur to save costs and does not provide any equipment to porters who work on their own and are paid by weight.
In addition, they do not touch a penny of the 30,000 rupees (2.50 euros) increase per camera, in addition to the entry of 15,000 rupees (1.20 euros), which the guards of this natural park charge tourists who come to photograph the volcano and its human mules.
“This job is for the animals, not the humans,” said Madrusin, a 42-year-old porter who has worked at Kawah Ijen for 30 years since he left college.
Able to carry up to 110 kilos, he assures that he will not stop working "as long as he can", because he needs money to raise his 3 sons, aged between 10 and 18 years.
I will not retire, I will die here because the volcano is my whole life.
Although sulfur damages the throat and irritates the eyes when the wind turns and traps the miners in the thick columns of smoke that come out of the volcano, they are so hardened that no one complains of suffering from serious diseases ... to which are obviously added their usual respiratory problems, osteoarthritis, pain in the knees and shoulders, deformed shoulders.
By balancing the basket on his back, the 53-year-old Unainik can only carry 50 kilos.
Every day, he and his companions extract 15 tons of sulfur from the volcano, which three trucks transport to the Tamansari warehouse, 18 kilometers away by a goat trail invaded by weeds.
“I will not retire, I will die here because the volcano is my whole life,” Unainik said, opening his mouth wide, revealing several missing teeth.
The eldest of her five children, aged 30, also works as a sulfur carrier.
Time passes, but the misery continues from generation to generation one of the most difficult jobs in the world: the one made by the human mules of the Kawah ljen volcano.
Singapore is looking for babies to save the economy
Singaporeans blame the lack of children on career, stress and the cost of home ownership.
"Singapore's population needs to grow."
I am a husband and a patriot, you are my wife and a patriot, let us fulfill our civic duty and give life!
It may seem unlikely that these lyrics come from an advertisement for mint lozenges, but despite this, or perhaps because of it, the video spread like wildfire on YouTube in Singapore earlier this year.
The lyrics come from a rap group that uses local references such as "Let's put a polichinelle in the drawer" to mock Singapore's birth rate.
BBH, the advertising agency behind the video, hopes to draw attention to the problem in a fun way through this ad.
Its creative director, Douglas Hamilton, said he wanted to use the power of music to get people to fulfill “their national duty.”
It is intended only for the Internet, so we were able to make it entertaining and fun.
This is the main problem in this country.
We are the worst in the world in the area of births, so we felt that this was a topic that we had to address.
We knew that the government had tried several things, such as launching pheromone perfumes or organizing speed-dating parties.
Many of these ideas were creative, but they didn’t necessarily work.
So we thought, what could be more creative to solve this problem than making it into a rap song?
1.2 children
The Singaporean government does not take it so lightly.
It spends $1,300 a year on policies to encourage its citizens to have more children.
A government measure in favor of marriages and fathers grants up to $15,000 per child, extends maternity leave and distributes tax benefits.
But all this had little effect.
Singapore is a wealthy, high-tech city-state in Southeast Asia, also known for the conservatism of its leaders and its strict social controls.
Singapore's birth rate, according to its national population distribution, currently stands at 1.2 children per woman.
The last time it was above 2, considered the renewal rate, was in 1976.
Why don’t Singaporeans have more children?
Tan Wei Ming, director of marriage and family policy at the National Population Division, says it’s due to “better education” and “a wider choice of career opportunities.”
“This has allowed people to have a wider range of options in terms of life goals and priorities, beyond marriage and starting a family,” she explains.
These changes in social norms have contributed to the increase in the number of singles and delaying marriage and births, resulting in a decrease in the birth rate in Singapore.
Meanwhile, an immigration policy aimed at radically increasing immigration to counter population decline has created resentment among the local population.
In Singapore, there are websites abounding with barely disguised xenophobia against new immigrants, especially Chinese who are accused of pulling wages down and failing to integrate.
The rise in immigration is also seen as one of the reasons why Singapore’s ruling party had its worst election results since independence last year.
Since the elections, they have tried to correct the problem by setting higher quotas and taxes for foreign workers.
Unexpected consequences
While the fall in the birth rate has known effects on a country’s economic growth, tax revenues, health costs and immigration policies, Singapore’s example also has unintended consequences.
The government is trying to avoid the construction of many small houses.
For example, this has begun to affect the real estate sector.
Urban development authorities have begun to control the number of small apartments, known as “shoe boxes”, that can be built in specific areas of the city.
These apartments have an area of 46 square meters and their sale is very successful.
However, authorities are concerned that they may promote a single lifestyle and discourage developers wishing to build large family homes.
But Lim Yew Soon, chief executive of real estate company EL Developers, says his “shoe boxes” are selling much faster than larger dwellings.
They are more popular, in the sense that these dwellings are built much faster than those of larger size.
For this reason, it is much more profitable for our treasury.
However, he admits that the new standards give clearer instructions to proponents, who were previously put in the wheel if they wanted to offer too many small dwellings in a project.
Too much stress
Singapore is a city-state.
If these new regulations can be a step towards increasing the national birth rate, by talking to Singaporeans who work in the financial district of the center, it would seem that they will not have much effect.
“People are very stressed, houses are expensive, and so is education, which is why people put it off,” says one young executive.
Other people can have children.
"But for me, it's important to be able to have my money and my time," says another young man in his twenties.
Men and women cite their careers, stress and the cost of home ownership and education as reasons why they cannot have children.
So while the government is trying to convince its citizens to have children, when it comes to making babies, Singaporeans themselves have the final say.
What is private offline is private online
Confidentiality
According to the Dictionary of the Royal Spanish Academy, it is about the quality of the private domain or "the area of private life that we can protect from any intrusion".
What is the private domain for children under 16 years of age?
How to apply this definition in everyday life and on social networks?
Does he understand the dangers to which he exposes himself by broadcasting events on the Internet that he would certainly not share offline?
The newspaper elPeri<0xC3><0xB3>dico interviewed five young boys, aged between 10 and 15 years, frequent users of the web.
In four of the cases, they associated the term “something very personal” on a personal level with “the password and username” when they applied it to social networks.
“I won’t reveal my most personal secrets in a post,” says Jorge, 10, when he tries to explain the meaning of the term private on sites like Facebook, Twitter, Hotmail and Windows Live Messenger, where he has had an account for two years.
“These are very secret secrets, my mother can know them but not everyone,” he says.
On FB, I post cool images or games.
I also talk to my friends.
“I won’t share one of my pictures or someone who would be a fool,” he said.
The young boy acknowledges that it is wrong to post obscene photos, naked people, crimes or write humiliating or violent comments.
Jorge says he knows his 35 friends on FB as well as his nine followers on Twitter.
Most of them are family.
Her mother is one of them, she knows the password to one of the accounts.
I opened a Twitter account to express myself and write interesting tweets.
“I don’t know if they answer me, I just post them,” he adds.
“Social media is fun, I can talk to distant relatives or friends, quickly,” he says.
He said he would never accept the request of an unknown person.
Nor will he trust someone who would recommend a stranger to him.
The case of 14-year-old Jose is different.
The teenager has accounts on Hotmail, Facebook, My Space and Ask, on the latter, he admits not knowing 20 of the people registered on his list of friends.
“It doesn’t worry me because we have something in common, music for example,” he says.
According to the young boy, no one made advances or asked him for his address or phone number.
“If they put pressure on me or demanded it, I would simply remove them from my account,” he said.
José subscribed to Ask after reading a recommendation on Twitter.
The experiences we know today as cyberbullying are not foreign to the young boy.
A friend of mine was hacked on a social network.
They threatened him and demanded money.
“He never knew who it was,” he said.
The victim, according to José, did not close his account.
"He only passed it on in a private profile."
He then explains a series of manipulations to set up his account safely.
Unlike Jorge, this young man would post pictures of acquaintances in uncomfortable or embarrassing situations.
Yes, I would if I was angry or angry.
“Even though I know it’s cyberbullying,” he says.
Key issues
Marielos Porras, English teacher and graduate in Education and Learning, believes that to guide children and adolescents, we must understand that the purpose of social networks is to inform.
"The Internet has emerged as a way to search for information, but with the emergence of these sites, the rule of the game has changed," she said.
Porras points out that academician Marc Prensky, who holds a master’s degree in pedagogy from Yale University and author of the book “Natives and Digital Immigrants,” uses these terms to explain the phenomenon.
Digital natives are the children and young people who were born with technology.
“We are the digital immigrants who have to teach them there, while we ourselves are learning,” she says.
He adds that the theme is complex, "because we ask them to have a defined criterion on what should or should not be disclosed, published or said at an age when they do not have the maturity to do so."
“We also ask them to be selective when what matters most to them is to be popular, to have thousands of friends without thinking about the consequences.”
According to the specialist, the most effective way to teach children and adolescents about privacy is to use questions that make them think.
“Telling them not to do it is useless,” she said.
Then Porras lists a few examples: there are things you wouldn’t tell a stranger, why do you do it on the Internet?
Or, would you like them to post a picture of you like that of a friend you posted?
Do you know what others post about you?
When you identify holiday photos, do you ask other people for permission to identify them?
And also, does everyone need to know what you are doing at every moment?
Another point is to make them understand that they have to act online as they do offline.
It's the same rules.
“Outside of the Internet, everyone must act with respect, morality and other principles, it must be the same on social networks,” she says.
Surveillance
Estuardo Guardia, a university professor, primary school teacher and education advisor, says that it is essential that parents read the conditions of use of social networks conscientiously.
By understanding each of the terms, they will have a solid foundation to discuss with their children the implications of opening an account on the Internet.
“For example, age and what is allowed to be shared or published,” he says.
According to Guardia, it is essential to remind children not to talk to strangers.
The UNASUR Summit ended without the Lima Declaration being made public
The 6th Presidential Summit of the Union of South American Nations (UNASUR) ended today in Peru without the Lima Declaration being made public, although it was previously announced and theoretically adopted by the 7 representatives present.
Efe has tried several times to access the document signed at the 6th Ordinary Meeting of Heads of State and Government of UNASUR, but the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and the Presidency initially indicated that it would be disclosed after the summit was closed, and then claimed that it would be published at any moment on the website of the Peruvian government.
When questioned about the text, they reported that its contents had been exposed by the President of Peru, Ollante Humala, during brief statements to the press.
Journalists' access to information about the summit has been constantly limited.
During the day, only the video without the sound of the presidential assembly with the message "private session, restricted audio" was broadcast in the press room.
The little information that circulated among the journalists was that given by the press attachés of some of the governments of Unasur who attended the meeting, with the exception of the Peruvian spokesman.
The only document released during the day was the list of presidents present, which caused some unease among the hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who were demanding more important information.
Later, Peru’s presidency sent an email to the media with the “final declaration” of the summit, but it was President Humala’s speech and not the official document that concluded the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the 3rd South American-Arab Summit (ASPA) and, on this occasion, although it was strongly requested by the press, it also did not release the declaration also called the Lima Declaration, as had been previously announced.
On the official website of the ASPA, it can be verified that the document was published last March.
In both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities have tried to put in place safe transmission systems for all journalists, but they have limited the collection of information as much as possible.
The summit also concluded with the joint agreement of Chile and Peru to accept a judgment of the Court of The Hague that settles a border dispute between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Pi<0xC3><0xB1>era, met at the regional meeting and said they would respect the ICJ's decision to hear the pleas of both parties in the trial that Lima has filed against Santiago and which begins Monday in The Hague.
“We will respect and execute the verdict that will resolve the disputes that we are bringing today before this international court,” Humala said, alongside his Chilean counterpart.
"Chile has always been, and will continue to be, a country that respects international law, the peaceful resolution of controversies, treaties and international tribunals," Pi<0xC3><0xB1>era said, shaking hands with Humala.
The confirmation of the two presidents that they would submit to the ICJ came after Colombia denounced this week the Bogota Pact by which it had agreed to submit to the decisions of this international tribunal, after a decision on maritime boundaries with Nicaragua that it considered to be seriously wrong.
The summit was held without the presence of the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff, Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, Bolivia, Evo Morales, and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, suspended from Unasur since 2011 after the ouster of its former president Fernando Lugo, did not participate in the meeting.
Host President Ollanta Humala was tasked with opening deliberations in the morning and closing the summit shortly after noon in Lima.
The representative read the final document in which he announced that 16 agreements had been adopted and that the lines of action of 31 projects had been set between the South American countries for a total of 17 million dollars of investment.
Among the agreements adopted, he mentioned that the UNASUR countries would put in place "important steps to achieve the goal of South American citizenship through the development of agreements on residence permits".
He informed that actions would be put in place to improve "cooperation in the fight against urban insecurity and international organized crime, actions for better access to medicines, low-cost Internet access throughout South America, and to jointly and effectively assess the risks of natural disasters."
With a Europe in crisis, "the economic consolidation (of Latin America) must not have a triumphalist matrix but must help increase our productive matrix and envision a better future for our people," concluded President Humala.
“We have decided to favor a group of 31 emblematic projects that improve the connection of the spaces of South America, especially in rural and border areas ... by uniting our countries and generating new economic circuits,” the Peruvian president said in a speech.
Among those projects, he mentioned that five concerned Peru and were on the transversal axes of its territory, from the coast to Brazil, and that two aimed at a greater connection with Ecuador, although he did not give more details.
Similarly, the outcome document mentions the political situation in Paraguay.
“We hope that the electoral process of this country will allow its reintegration into the Union of South American Nations,” from which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain a region of prosperity and peace, integrated and having good relations with its neighbours, is another theme addressed at the summit.
In this sense, the Colombian president, Juan Manuel Santos, said, before starting the regional meeting, that he hoped to meet his Nicaraguan counterpart, Daniel Ortega, the following Saturday in Mexico City to calmly discuss the maritime dispute through an ICJ judgment requested by Bogota.
“It is possible that tomorrow (Saturday) I have a meeting with President Daniel Ortega,” Santos said.
“We will review all these ways, they are not exhaustive, including the treaty with Nicaragua that will ask to have a discussion with that country,” he stressed.
“I hope I can tell President Ortega that we will resolve this in the most civilized and respectful way possible,” Santos said.
Presidents Santos and Ortega will meet Saturday in Mexico City where they plan to attend the inauguration of the country's new president, Enrique Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto.
Similarly, in the framework of the summit, the defense ministers of the bloc will meet in advance to approve the 2013 Action Plan, which attempts to strengthen dialogue and consensus in terms of defense in the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay are part of UNASUR, although the latter country is suspended.
Peru holds the presidency pro tempore of the regional bloc.
