AIDS-related deaths today are due to late detection.
Fabrizio was 21 years old when he was confirmed as HIV positive.
"It's as if the sky has fallen on my head," he said, referring to the time of the announcement, which the doctor had tried to make "less painful", in vain.
The young man hid it from his family.
He decided to take care of his illness on his own and began to learn about it and his relentlessness was such that he just celebrated his 43rd birthday.
He is, without a doubt, one of the oldest patients of the HIV unit of the Civil Hospital of Guadalajara (HCG), in which he found himself in 1994 after many battles.
Fabrizio has been living with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) for 22 years, something difficult to imagine in the early 1990s, where there was a lot of doubt, little choice of treatment and more stigma.
Then, even the director of an IMSS clinic avoided saying goodbye “because he was speechless”.
At that time, having AIDS was synonymous with death.
Today, it is possible to survive this syndrome and have a good quality of life.
However, ignoring their illness, many people still arrive when the virus has already caused damage, "depleted" their immune system and are victims of opportunistic infections.
31 years after the appearance of AIDS in the world, in any case after the first reported cases, "the great victory today is that the survival of a patient who has started treatment at the right time and the survival of the population in general is exactly the same," said the head of the HIV unit of the HCG, Jaime Andrade Villanueva in a scientific reference that this information was validated in April of this year.
Infectiologist and HIV/AIDS expert Andrade Villanueva commented that since 2008, scientists have concluded that AIDS is no longer a life-threatening disease, but that the number of years of survival and quality of life depends on the level of immune system involvement presented by patients up to 200 at the time of diagnosis, with better prospects for those who do not consume a CD for 50 years and for those who do not consume a CD for up to 30 years.
To put it simply, this means that for someone who would receive an HIV positive diagnosis at age 25, “as long as it remains under control, will be able to live without problems up to 75 years,” explained the scientist interviewed.
In order to put this progress in context, it is necessary to know that the life expectancy of Mexicans today is 76 years on average.
While it is true that mortality has decreased significantly in recent years, in the case of Mexico, the number of people dying from AIDS has increased from 6,678 in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (according to the UNAIDS annual report), but it is also true that, since the onset of AIDS, 60% of the patients identified on the national database have died.
In Jalisco alone, 255 people died in 2011, and there were 187 deaths as of May this year; however, we are assured that access to antiretroviral drugs has been universal since 2005.
So why are there still deaths?
I don't think the problem comes from access to treatment.
That's how I see it, that's what happened in our hospital.
In the last 12 years at least, we have never run out of drugs, the problem is that patients come to very advanced stages because they do not know that they are infected, or else they learn it in advanced stages of the disease.
“Nine out of ten patients arrive when they already have an opportunistic infection, what is needed to have a greater impact on overall mortality is to carry out earlier diagnoses and, for this, it is necessary to offer screening tests in a massive way, to all those who request it.”
Specialists and members of the State Council for AIDS Prevention of Jalisco (Coesida) agree on his proposal, as do patients themselves, such as Fabrizio, who had to do his screening test in a private laboratory, simply because a friend had done it and that, despite his young age, he was already a carrier of AIDS and suffered from Kaposi's sarcoma.
Everything changes when you learn that you have AIDS.
Some people think they're going to die and don't want to know.
“If I’m going to die, I’d better have fun three times a week,” they say, not me.
The change has been beneficial, I eat well, I exercise, I take my medication.
To this day, his parents only know that he has cancer.
I have a normal life, just like anyone else.
"I work, I have many activities, I travel, I have an active sex life, but co-responsible, I pay attention to myself and the other person," says Fabrizio, who agreed to share his intimacy with MILENIO JALISCO to help, thanks to his testimony, those who are afraid today, during the World AIDS Day march.
Whether they do the test, if they have taken risks, the sooner they will know if they are HIV-positive and the better it will be, and if they already have the diagnosis, they must know that we can live like everyone else, by being responsible.
His message summarizes the slogan of the battle against AIDS in this year 2012.
Condoms on the counter
There are many gaps between health programs and the ordinary citizen, says Ricardo Salazar, a journalist from Guadalajara who has embraced the cause of HIV.
And the biggest one is prevention.
