A judgment upheld on appeal by a U.S. court ignores the restructuring of the Vitro group’s debt through a commercial bankruptcy in Mexico, setting a bad precedent for all domestic companies with branches in the neighboring country and with solvency problems.
It therefore seems that the survival procedures of the companies authorized by Mexican law are not valid in the country with the star-studded banner, in contravention of international agreements.
From a practical point of view, the blow to the judgment delivered on June 15 by Judge Harlin Hale of the Bankruptcy Court for the Northern District of Texas, leaves Mexican companies defenseless against the possibility of embargo of their properties beyond the Bravo.
However, the resolution will allow Mexico’s top glass maker to take the case to the U.S. Supreme Court based on three inconsistencies.
First, while the judge in the case points out that creditors must register under the United States Bankruptcy Act, the Fifth Circuit Court of Appeals, sitting in New Orleans, states that the main proceeding is formalized commercial bankruptcy in Mexico.
The first point would involve denouncing international procedural cooperation in cases of insolvency of companies with a transnational profile.
Indeed, the United Nations Model Law for the Uniformity of International Commercial Law had been created for this purpose by using the American Law Institute as an arbitrator.
In the second place, the judgment establishes that without the intercompany vote, recognized in the critical mass of commercial bankruptcy, the debts contracted by subsidiaries of Vitro to the parent company, the majority required for the approval of the restructuring could not have been obtained.
However, Mexican laws recognize this possibility.
In fact, the Vitro case is not the first to use this plan.
There are a half-dozen examples here, among them Agremex and Comercial Mexicana, whose debts were guaranteed by the Federal Institute of Commercial Bankruptcy.
Moreover, what is certain is that, since there remained the votes of the subsidiaries, in any case the creditors of Vitro who fought against this in the courts of the United States, that is to say the “vautour” funds such as Aurelios Capital, Aurelios Convergencia, Elliot Internacional and Liverpool Limited, would not have obtained a majority.
The vote would have been 45 to 37.
An information omitted by the appellate court.
On the other hand, Vitro was blamed for the difficult situation he had been facing since 2008 without stopping at the serious economic crisis facing the United States, passing on the costs to the country.
For now, the González Sada family company will appeal to the same appeals court for the vote to be taken in its entirety, that is, with the five magistrates, since only three had voted.
The insurance claim will claim non-prosperity and require review of the lawsuit by a higher court, in this case the U.S. Supreme Court.
The most serious is that the court ignored a document sent by the Government of Mexico on behalf of the amicus curiae (“friend of the Court”) detailing Vitro’s procedure under the Commercial Bankruptcy Act, noting that it freed him from the conventions signed by the two countries to put him on the same level as paragraph 15 of the United States Bankruptcy Act.
In addition, he pointed out that the country had complied with the principles of the United Nations Commission on International Trade, i.e. the rules established for cross-border insolvency cases, which ensured fairness for debtors and creditors.
Carambolage of two parts: they knock out Vitro and they knock out the country.
